{"title_page": "Maanja Velu", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Maanja Velu\n| film name      = {{film name|ta|\u0bae\u0bbe\u0b9e\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbe \u0bb5\u0bc7\u0bb2\u0bc1}}\n| image          = Maanja Velu.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[A. Venkatesh (director)|A. Venkatesh]]\n| writer         = [[Pattukkottai Prabakar]] (dialogues)\n| story          = [[Sriwass]]\n| starring       = {{unbulleted list|[[Arun Vijay]]|[[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]]|[[Prabhu Ganesan|Prabhu]]|[[Dhansika]]|[[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]]|[[Vijayakumar (actor)|Vijayakumar]]|[[Riyaz Khan]]|[[Ganja Karuppu]]|[[Anu Haasan]]}}\n| producer       = {{unbulleted list|Mrs. Susil Mohan|M. Hemanth}}\n| music          = [[Mani Sharma]]\n| cinematography = [[A. Venkatesh (cinematography)|A. Venkatesh]]\n| editing        = [[V. T. Vijayan]]\n| studio         = Feather Touch Entertainments\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2010|5|21}}\n| language       = Tamil\n| country        = India\n}}\n'''''Maanja Velu''''' is a 2010 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[action film]] directed by [[A. Venkatesh (director)|A. Venkatesh]]. It stars [[Arun Vijay]], [[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]], [[Prabhu Ganesan|Prabhu]] and [[Dhansika]] in the lead with [[Vijayakumar (actor)|Vijayakumar]] and [[Riyaz Khan]] playing supporting roles and [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] and [[Ganja Karuppu]] providing comical relief. Most of the team from the successful venture, ''[[Malai Malai]]'' re-united for this film. It is a remake of the 2007 [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu film]] ''[[Lakshyam (2007 film)|Lakshyam]]''.<ref name=\"Indiaglitz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/52337.html |title=Tollywood's Lakshyam is Maanja Velu|publisher=Indiaglitz |date=2009-12-04 |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> It has also been dubbed in Hindi as ''Zakhmi Cheetah''. The film became a hit at the box office similar to the previous outing ''[[Malai Malai]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nThe film starts with a flashback. ACP Bose ([[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]]) is a sincere police officer happily married. He lives with his parents and younger brother Velu ([[Arun Vijay]]). Velu is a college student, and he falls in love with his classmate Anjali ([[Dhansika]]). Enters Umapathi ([[Chandrasekar]]), the villain who is notorious for settlements and land deals. Anjali comes across Bose when she is on a field trip from her college with her friends. She gets friendly with his daughter Pinky, who tells her that she would get her introduced to her uncle Velu, and they would make a good pair. It turns out that Velu studies in Anjali's college and soon after, they come to know each other and get close.\n\nBose investigate the case of Umapathi, whom no one has been able to touch. He is even involved with a land deal involving crores of money which is completely illegal and others including the DIG is involved. When the chairman of the bank who has lent money for the deal demands the money back as the deal has not worked, Umapathi eliminates him. The people who are customers of the bank take to the streets and try to damage the bank. Bose arrives there, arrests the manager, and takes him away. Somehow, Umapathi comes to know where the manager has been taken. He arrives there with his men and the DIG and nearly kills Bose. Umapathi asks his men to dump the body. On the way, Velu gets involved and ultimately rescues Bose from a burning bus, and Bose dies in Velu's arms. The entire media and the people think Bose has swindled off all the money as they have been made to believe that by the DIG.\n\nVelu decides to take revenge on the people who killed his brother. Firstly he kills Dinesh (Hemanth), his friend and Umapathi's henchman. Then he kills the DIG (he had been taken to jail and he had escaped). Umapathi also kidnaps Velu's entire family. Velu goes to an old temple where he kills Umapathi. He spills the beans that Bose is dead, and he rescues his family under the supervision of the new DIG Gautham Ganesh ([[Prabhu Ganesan|Prabhu]]), who supports him wholeheartedly.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Arun Vijay]] as Velu\n* [[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]] as ACP Subash Chandra Bose aka ACP Bose\n* [[Prabhu Ganesan|Prabhu]] as Gautham Ganesh, the new DIG\n* [[Dhansika]] as Anjali\n* [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] as Manickam\n* [[Vagai Chandrasekhar|Chandrashekar]] as Umapathi\n* Hemanth as Dinesh\n* [[Riyaz Khan]] as Easwara Pandian\n* [[Ilavarasu]] as Sivagnanam\n* [[Ganja Karuppu]] as Bhooshan\n* [[Vijayakumar (actor)|Vijayakumar]] as Velu's father\n* [[Meera Krishnan]] as Velu's mother\n* [[Anu Haasan]] as Bose's wife\n* [[Nizhalgal Ravi]] as Anjali's father\n* [[Shakeela]] as Manikkam and Bhooshan's mother\n* [[Lollu Sabha Manohar]] as Manikkam and Bhooshan's father\n* [[R. S. Shivaji]]  as Avatar mama\n* [[Thyagu (actor)|Thyagu]]\n* [[Singamuthu]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Production==\nAfter the success of his film ''[[Malai Malai]]'', [[Arun Vijay]] teams with Malai Malai team (consists of A Venkatesh, Mani Sharma, Santhanam and producer Mohan) for second time, Venkatesh decided to remake the Telugu film ''[[Lakshyam (2007 film)|Lakshyam]]''.<ref name=\"Indiaglitz\"/> The film was said to be titled as ''Maanja Madhan''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/48954.html |title=Arun Vijay is 'Maanja Madhan' - Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> which proved untrue and it is changed as ''Maanja Velu''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/arun-vijay-in-stylish-action-thriller-movie.htm |title=Arun Vijay in stylish action Thriller movie&#124;Maanja Velu Film&#124;Movies |publisher=Movies.sulekha.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120711112355/http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/arun-vijay-in-stylish-action-thriller-movie.htm |archive-date=11 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/feather-touch-roped-in-arun-vijay.htm |title=Feather Touch Roped in Arun Vijay&#124;Maanja Velu Film&#124;Movies |publisher=Movies.sulekha.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/masala/hotnews/new/03092009-2.shtml |title=Dailynews&nbsp;\u2014 Arun becomes 'Manja Velu' |publisher=Cinesouth.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref>\n\n[[Suresh Gopi]] was initially selected to play the role of Arun's elder brother<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/49921.html |title=Suresh Gopi in 'Maanja Velu' - Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> but he was replaced by another senior actor [[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]] who made his comeback through this film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/50116.html |title=Karthik-Prabhu again for \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 - Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14922345 |title=Manja Velu is almost complete!|publisher=Sify |date=2009-12-04 |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.top10cinema.com/news/1132/karthik-returns-with-maanja-velu |title=Karthik Returns With Maanja Velu &#124; News&nbsp;\u2014 General |publisher=Top 10 Cinema |date=2009-09-30 |accessdate=2011-10-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009022400/http://www.top10cinema.com/news/1132/karthik-returns-with-maanja-velu |archivedate=9 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Dhansika, who was one of the five girls in ''[[Peraanmai]]'' has been selected to play the pair opposite hero making her first project as a solo heroine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southdreamz.com/2009/11/actress-dhanshika-shoots-for-maanja-velu.html |title=Actress Dhanshika shoots for maanja velu |publisher=Southdreamz.com |date=2009-11-09 |accessdate=2012-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625192328/http://www.southdreamz.com/2009/11/actress-dhanshika-shoots-for-maanja-velu.html |archivedate=25 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.top10cinema.com/news/1141/peraanmai-heroine-teams-with-arun-vijay |title=Peraanmai Heroine Teams With Arun Vijay &#124; News&nbsp;\u2014 General |publisher=Top 10 Cinema |date=2009-10-01 |accessdate=2012-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004022237/http://www.top10cinema.com/news/1141/peraanmai-heroine-teams-with-arun-vijay |archivedate=4 October 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFirst schedule of the film was started with song at Bangkok.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/52252.html |title=\u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 is up and running&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/news/2009/arun-vijay-sky-diving-040909.html |title=Arun Vijay to learn Sky diving in London! |publisher=OneIndia |date=2009-09-04 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> The climax fight scenes of the film was canned in Ekkattuthangal Burma Colony Muneeswarar Temple, Chennai for last 5 days and it was shot using two outdoor units and four cameras, the set was built like that of a ruined temple with a 50&nbsp;ft tall 'Aiyanaar' statue was erected at a whoping 65 lakhs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/53757.html |title=Maanja Velu\u2019s fulsome climax&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> A scene featuring 400 junior artists and 25 stunt artists was canned in a festival set that was erected around the temple. A scene in which Arun Vijay kicking two fighters by jumping from a platform was being shot, for which both the fighters were tied on with a transparent nylon rope, to avoid accidents. Unexpectedly one of the nylon ropes got tangled with Arun Vijay's right arm while he was performing the action. Arun Vijay's elbow was badly injured due to the accident and the whole arm swell at once. Immediately the actor was offered first aid by the stunt master Kanal Kannan and was rushed to the hospital where he was offered emergency treatment, for this scene Arun tonsured his head to give a new look and also hanged upside down which was shot for 7 days.<ref name=\"indiaglitz1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videos.behindwoods.com/videos-q1-09/actor-actress-interview/arun-vijay.html|title=Arun Vijay interview|publisher= Behindwoods}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jan-10-01/arun-vijay-maanja-velu-kanal-kannan-07-01-10.html |title=Actor tonsures his head&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News&nbsp;\u2014 Arun Vijay &#124; Maanja Velu &#124; Kanal Kannan |publisher=Behindwoods |date=2010-01-07 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Songs were shot at Pazhani, Dindigul and Chennai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/52132.html |title=Arun Vijay injured at \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 shoot&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> The title song of the film was shot in Pondicherry schedule with 80 junior artists. Few stunts were shot at Trichy and Stunt master Kanal Kannan has given 45 days of his schedule.<ref name=\"indiaglitz1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/52924.html |title=\u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 moves to Trichy&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nBefore the release, Dr. Kalidoss has stated that he had been in the film industry for the past 15 years and that he completed a film titled \u2018Thunichal\u2019 with Arun Vijay in the lead in the year 2008. He also stated that though the Censor Board had cleared the film, Arun Vijay had \u2018purposely\u2019 delayed the release of the film by not completing his portion of the \u2018dubbing\u2019 work. As he had spent Rs.2 crores till date, the producer told Vijay that he couldn't continue to shoot the film. Meanwhile, he was asked by the actor to release Thunichal after his \u2018Malai Malai\u2019 released. Due to his non-cooperation, instead of releasing \u2018Thunichal\u2019 in 160 theatres, I could release the film only in 16 theatres on 1 January this year, said Kalidoss. Due to this, I incurred a loss of Rs.1.5 crores, he added. \"Due to the mental harassment I had to endure because of Arun Vijay, I couldn\u2019t continue my profession as a doctor for the past 4 years. Vijay has to pay me Rs.1.5 crores and till he does so, the release of his \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 should be stayed till the 19th of this month,\" he had stated in the petition<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/arun-vijay-s-maanja-velu-is-stayed-by-hc.htm |title=Arun Vijay's 'Maanja Velu' is stayed by HC&#124;Maanja Velu Film&#124;Movies |publisher=Movies.sulekha.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> \nDr. Mohan, producer of \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 and father-in-law of Arun Vijay, had filed a counter petition with the Court praying for vacation of the stay on the grounds that he, as a producer, had nothing to do with Dr. Kalidoss\u2019 case and requested that as such, his film should be allowed to release on the stipulated date. Advocate G. Murugesh Kumar, who appeared on behalf of Dr. Mohan in the court of Mr. Justice T.S. Sivagnanam, managed to putforth his point of view strongly before the Judge and said that Dr. Kalidoss had \u2018wrongly informed\u2019 the Court in the matter. As soon as the Judge announced that he'd be giving the verdict based on the \u2018actual nature\u2019 of the case, Dr. Kalidoss is said to have \u2018withdrawn\u2019 his petition from the Court. Following this, the Judge dismissed the petition and said that the film could release on 21 May as per its original schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/high-court-clears-hurdles-in-release-of-maanja-velu.htm |title=High Court clears hurdles in release of 'Maanja Velu'&#124;Maanja Velu Film&#124;Movies |publisher=Movies.sulekha.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Maanja Velu\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Mani Sharma]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Front Cover\n| released   =\n| recorded   = Gemini Music\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Junglee Music\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe soundtrack is composed by [[Mani Sharma]] and he reused the tunes from the original film ''[[Lakshyam (2007 film)|Lakshyam]]''. Audio function was attended by Producers Council chief Rama Narayanan, secretary Sivasakthi pandian, director Shakthi Chidambaram, actors [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]], [[Shaam (actor)|Shaam]], [[Jai (actor)|Jai]], [[Sibiraj]], [[Sundar C.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/55267.html |title=\u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 marks his presence&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Performer(s)\n| title1 = Munneru Munneru\n| extra1 = [[Ranjith (singer)|Ranjith]], Naveen\n| lyrics1 = [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]]\n| title2 = Eppadi Thaan Muraichu\n| extra2 = [[Rahul Nambiar]]\n| lyrics2 = Vaali\n| title3 = Maanja Maanja\n| extra3 = [[Tippu (singer)|Tippu]], [[Sujatha Mohan|Sujatha]]\n| lyrics3 = Vaali\n| title4 = Oh My Dear\n| extra4 = Ranjith, [[Saindhavi]]\n| lyrics4 = [[Viveka (lyricist)|Viveka]]\n| title5 = Ooril Ulla Uyirghalelaam\n| extra5 = [[Karthik (singer)|Karthik]]\n| lyrics5 = Vaali\n| title6 = Maanja Maanja\n| note6  = Retro Remix\n| extra6 = Mukesh, Priya Subramaniam\n| lyrics6 = Vaali\n}}\n\n===Critical response===\nThe soundtrack was released to generally positive reviews. Behindwoods said, \"there is nothing in the album that will make it stand up for itself\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-music-reviews/review-1/maanja-velu-arun-vijay.html |title=Maanja Velu&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Music Reviews |publisher=Behindwoods |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Milliblog said, \"getting 3 decent tracks in a masala potboiler soundtrack is a huge win indeed\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://itwofs.com/milliblog/2010/03/16/music-review-maanja-velu-tamil-manisharma/ |title=Music review: Maanja Velu (Tamil&nbsp;\u2013 Manisharma) by Milliblog! |publisher=Itwofs.com |date=2010-03-16 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Indiaglitz said, \"Over all, the music of Maanja Velu will definitely be chart busters and the music will have a wide reach. Mani Sharma, has used the tunes of his hit songs in Telugu in this album, which would surely appeal even to the Tamil audience\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/musicreview/11477.html |title=Maanja Velu Music Review songs lyrics |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date=2010-03-13 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe satellite rights of the film were sold to [[Kalaignar TV|Kalaignar]]. The film was given an \"A\" certificate by the [[Indian Censor Board]] and released on 21 May 2010 alongside ''[[Magane En Marumagane]]'', ''[[Kanakavel Kaaka]]'', ''[[Kutti Pisasu]]'', ''[[Kola Kolaya Mundhirika]]'' and ''[[Police Police|Kutrapirivu]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/movies/More-movies-in-May-news-tamil-kkfqA0cjijf.html |title=More movies in May|publisher=Sify |date=2010-05-04 |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref>\n\n===Reviews===\nSify said, \"On the whole director Venkatesh has dished out an average run of the mill mass masala cocktail which is quite entertaining in the first half but fizzles out in the second half with a predictable long drawn out climax\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/maanja-velu-review-tamil-14942723.html |title=Movie Review:Maanja Velu|publisher=Sify |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Behindwoods said, \"Maanja Velu is an entertainer that aims to satisfy all types of audiences and A. Venkatesh has managed to create a screenplay that takes care of all requirements. But, there is a feeling that the full potential of the script has not been realized. It is still a decent entertainer which can be watched especially for its wonderful casting\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-reviews/reviews-2/maanja-velu-arun-vijay-prabhu.html |title=Maanja Velu&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie Reviews |publisher=Behindwoods |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Times of India said, \"The one thing that strikes you about Maanja Velu is what a talent house Tamil cinema has been. As you watch the parade of the seniors like Karthik, Prabhu, Vijaykumar and Vagai Chandrasekhar you feel glad that they came up with good, great, moving or simply lovable performances in the past. It does a lot to ease the heart burn caused by the so-called earthy cinema that we have been treated to for months and months now. Where you saw plenty of victims of circumstances on display, but so very lacking in angst that you came away from the movie without any emotional connect\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/tamil/Maanja-Velu/movie-review/5968741.cms |title=Maanja Velu movie review|publisher=The Times of India|date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Indiaglitz said, \"A perfect one for those who love masala flicks\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/review/11477.html |title=Maanja Velu Tamil Movie Review |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date=2010-05-22 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Chennaionline said, \"Maanja Velu has all the ingredients of a masala flick but the problem is that it has no novelty or neatness to impress us\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chennaionline.com/movies/movie-reviews/20102527102500/Movie-Review-Maanja-Velu.col |title=Movie Review: \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 |publisher=ChennaiOnline |date=2010-05-27 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Top 10 cinema said, \"The movie may have its reach amongst the commercial film lovers, who have no regards for logics\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.top10cinema.com/review/4680/maanja-velu |title=Maanja Velu &#124; Movie Review |publisher=Top 10 Cinema |date=2010-05-24 |accessdate=2012-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527100635/http://www.top10cinema.com/review/4680/maanja-velu |archivedate=27 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nThe film has seen an above average opening with total collections running up to Rs. 18 lakhs and weekend collections at Rs. 3,38,177 in second week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://600024.com/specials/chennai-box-office-collections-%e2%80%93-may-28-30/9/ |title=Special \u00bb Chennai Box Office Collections&nbsp;\u2013 May 28\u201330 |publisher=600024.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref> After that, weekend saw Rs. 4,22,307 drawn in its favor with Rs. 26 lakhs over the last weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://600024.com/specials/chennai-box-office-collections-june-04-06/5/ |title=Special \u00bb Chennai Box Office Collections June 04\u201306 |publisher=600024.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref> Rs. 1,76,967 was made by the film this weekend with Rs. 32 lakhs spanning over 3 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://600024.com/specials/chennai-box-office-collections-june-11-to-13/3/ |title=Special \u00bb Chennai Box Office Collections June 11 to 13 |publisher=600024.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref> Total collections in Chennai was Rs. 26 lakhs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-slide-shows/movie-4/top-ten-movies-june-07/tamil-cinema-topten-movie-maanja-velu.html |title=Maanja Velu&nbsp;\u2014 Behindwoods.com&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Top Ten Movies&nbsp;\u2014 Maanja Velu Singam Sura Goripalayam Kanagavel Kakka |publisher=Behindwoods |date= |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref> Overall trade pundits declared the film as \"decent hit\" due to the medium budget it was produced on.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=4316170}}\n\n{{A. Venkatesh (director)}}\n\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Tamil remakes of Telugu films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tiruchirappalli]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:2010s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Tamil film scores by Mani Sharma]]\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Masala films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tiruchirappalli]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Tamil Nadu Police]]\n[[Category:Indian nonlinear narrative films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Maanja Velu\n| film name      = {{film name|ta|\u0bae\u0bbe\u0b9e\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbe \u0bb5\u0bc7\u0bb2\u0bc1}}\n| image          = Maanja Velu.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[A. Venkatesh (director)|A. Venkatesh]]\n| writer         = [[Pattukkottai Prabakar]] (dialogues)\n| story          = [[Sriwass]]\n| starring       = {{unbulleted list|[[Arun Vijay]]|[[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]]|[[Prabhu Ganesan|Prabhu]]|[[Dhansika]]|[[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]]|[[Vijayakumar (actor)|Vijayakumar]]|[[Riyaz Khan]]|[[Ganja Karuppu]]|[[Anu Haasan]]}}\n| producer       = {{unbulleted list|Mrs. Susil Mohan|M. Hemanth}}\n| music          = [[Mani Sharma]]\n| cinematography = [[A. Venkatesh (cinematography)|A. Venkatesh]]\n| editing        = [[V. T. Vijayan]]\n| studio         = Feather Touch Entertainments\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2010|5|21}}\n| language       = Tamil\n| country        = India\n}}\n'''''Maanja Velu''''' is a 2010 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[action film]] directed by [[A. Venkatesh (director)|A. Venkatesh]]. It stars [[Arun Vijay]], [[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]], [[Prabhu Ganesan|Prabhu]] and [[Dhansika]] in the lead with [[Vijayakumar (actor)|Vijayakumar]] and [[Riyaz Khan]] playing supporting roles and [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] and [[Ganja Karuppu]] providing comical relief. Most of the team from the successful venture, ''[[Malai Malai]]'' re-united for this film. It is a remake of the 2007 [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu film]] ''[[Lakshyam (2007 film)|Lakshyam]]''.<ref name=\"Indiaglitz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/52337.html |title=Tollywood's Lakshyam is Maanja Velu|publisher=Indiaglitz |date=2009-12-04 |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> It has also been dubbed in Hindi as ''Zakhmi Cheetah''. The film became a hit at the box office similar to the previous outing ''[[Malai Malai]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nThe film starts with a flashback. ACP Bose ([[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]]) is a sincere police officer happily married. He lives with his parents and younger brother Velu ([[Arun Vijay]]). Velu is a college student, and he falls in love with his classmate Anjali ([[Dhansika]]). Enters Umapathi ([[Chandrasekar]]), the villain who is notorious for settlements and land deals. Anjali comes across Bose when she is on a field trip from her college with her friends. She gets friendly with his daughter Pinky, who tells her that she would get her introduced to her uncle Velu, and they would make a good pair. It turns out that Velu studies in Anjali\u2019s college and soon after, they come to know each other and get close.\n\nBose investigate the case of Umapathi, whom no one has been able to touch. He is even involved with a land deal involving crores of money which is completely illegal and others including the DIG is involved. When the chairman of the bank who has lent money for the deal demands the money back as the deal has not worked, Umapathi eliminates him. The people who are customers of the bank take to the streets and try to damage the bank. Bose arrives there, arrests the manager, and takes him away. Somehow, Umapathi comes to know where the manager has been taken. He arrives there with his men and the DIG and nearly kills Bose. Umapathi asks his men to dump the body. On the way, Velu gets involved and ultimately rescues Bose from a burning bus, and Bose dies in Velu\u2019s arms. The entire media and the people think Bose has swindled off all the money as they have been made to believe that by the DIG.\n\nVelu decides to take revenge on the people who killed his brother. Firstly he kills Dinesh (Hemanth), his friend and Umapathi\u2019s henchman. Then he kills the DIG (he had been taken to jail and he had escaped). Umapathi also kidnaps Velu's entire family. Velu goes to an old temple where he kills Umapathi. He spills the beans that Bose is dead, and he rescues his family under the supervision of the new DIG Gautham Ganesh ([[Prabhu Ganesan|Prabhu]]), who supports him wholeheartedly.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Arun Vijay]] as Velu\n* [[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]] as ACP Subash Chandra Bose aka ACP Bose\n* [[Prabhu Ganesan|Prabhu]] as Gautham Ganesh, the new DIG\n* [[Dhansika]] as Anjali\n* [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] as Manickam\n* [[Vagai Chandrasekhar|Chandrashekar]] as Umapathi\n* Hemanth as Dinesh\n* [[Riyaz Khan]] as Easwara Pandian\n* [[Ilavarasu]] as Sivagnanam\n* [[Ganja Karuppu]] as Bhooshan\n* [[Vijayakumar (actor)|Vijayakumar]] as Velu's father\n* [[Meera Krishnan]] as Velu's mother\n* [[Anu Haasan]] as Bose's wife\n* [[Nizhalgal Ravi]] as Anjali's father\n* [[Shakeela]] as Manikkam and Bhooshan's mother\n* [[Lollu Sabha Manohar]] as Manikkam and Bhooshan's father\n* [[R. S. Shivaji]]  as Avatar mama\n\n* [[Thyagu (actor)|Thyagu]]\n* [[Singamuthu]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Production==\nAfter the success of his film ''[[Malai Malai]]'', [[Arun Vijay]] teams with Malai Malai team (consists of A Venkatesh, Mani Sharma, Santhanam and producer Mohan) for second time, Venkatesh decided to remake the Telugu film ''[[Lakshyam (2007 film)|Lakshyam]]''.<ref name=\"Indiaglitz\"/> The film was said to be titled as ''Maanja Madhan''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/48954.html |title=Arun Vijay is 'Maanja Madhan' - Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> which proved untrue and it is changed as ''Maanja Velu''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/arun-vijay-in-stylish-action-thriller-movie.htm |title=Arun Vijay in stylish action Thriller movie&#124;Maanja Velu Film&#124;Movies |publisher=Movies.sulekha.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120711112355/http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/arun-vijay-in-stylish-action-thriller-movie.htm |archive-date=11 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/feather-touch-roped-in-arun-vijay.htm |title=Feather Touch Roped in Arun Vijay&#124;Maanja Velu Film&#124;Movies |publisher=Movies.sulekha.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/masala/hotnews/new/03092009-2.shtml |title=Dailynews&nbsp;\u2014 Arun becomes 'Manja Velu' |publisher=Cinesouth.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref>\n\n[[Suresh Gopi]] was initially selected to play the role of Arun's elder brother<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/49921.html |title=Suresh Gopi in 'Maanja Velu' - Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> but he was replaced by another senior actor [[Karthik Muthuraman|Karthik]] who made his comeback through this film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/50116.html |title=Karthik-Prabhu again for \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 - Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14922345 |title=Manja Velu is almost complete!|publisher=Sify |date=2009-12-04 |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.top10cinema.com/news/1132/karthik-returns-with-maanja-velu |title=Karthik Returns With Maanja Velu &#124; News&nbsp;\u2014 General |publisher=Top 10 Cinema |date=2009-09-30 |accessdate=2011-10-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009022400/http://www.top10cinema.com/news/1132/karthik-returns-with-maanja-velu |archivedate=9 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Dhansika, who was one of the five girls in ''[[Peraanmai]]'' has been selected to play the pair opposite hero making her first project as a solo heroine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southdreamz.com/2009/11/actress-dhanshika-shoots-for-maanja-velu.html |title=Actress Dhanshika shoots for maanja velu |publisher=Southdreamz.com |date=2009-11-09 |accessdate=2012-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625192328/http://www.southdreamz.com/2009/11/actress-dhanshika-shoots-for-maanja-velu.html |archivedate=25 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.top10cinema.com/news/1141/peraanmai-heroine-teams-with-arun-vijay |title=Peraanmai Heroine Teams With Arun Vijay &#124; News&nbsp;\u2014 General |publisher=Top 10 Cinema |date=2009-10-01 |accessdate=2012-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004022237/http://www.top10cinema.com/news/1141/peraanmai-heroine-teams-with-arun-vijay |archivedate=4 October 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFirst schedule of the film was started with song at Bangkok.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/52252.html |title=\u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 is up and running&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/news/2009/arun-vijay-sky-diving-040909.html |title=Arun Vijay to learn Sky diving in London! |publisher=OneIndia |date=2009-09-04 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> The climax fight scenes of the film was canned in Ekkattuthangal Burma Colony Muneeswarar Temple, Chennai for last 5 days and it was shot using two outdoor units and four cameras, the set was built like that of a ruined temple with a 50&nbsp;ft tall 'Aiyanaar' statue was erected at a whoping 65 lakhs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/53757.html |title=Maanja Velu\u2019s fulsome climax&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> A scene featuring 400 junior artists and 25 stunt artists was canned in a festival set that was erected around the temple. A scene in which Arun Vijay kicking two fighters by jumping from a platform was being shot, for which both the fighters were tied on with a transparent nylon rope, to avoid accidents. Unexpectedly one of the nylon ropes got tangled with Arun Vijay's right arm while he was performing the action. Arun Vijay's elbow was badly injured due to the accident and the whole arm swell at once. Immediately the actor was offered first aid by the stunt master Kanal Kannan and was rushed to the hospital where he was offered emergency treatment, for this scene Arun tonsured his head to give a new look and also hanged upside down which was shot for 7 days.<ref name=\"indiaglitz1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videos.behindwoods.com/videos-q1-09/actor-actress-interview/arun-vijay.html|title=Arun Vijay interview|publisher= Behindwoods}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jan-10-01/arun-vijay-maanja-velu-kanal-kannan-07-01-10.html |title=Actor tonsures his head&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News&nbsp;\u2014 Arun Vijay &#124; Maanja Velu &#124; Kanal Kannan |publisher=Behindwoods |date=2010-01-07 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Songs were shot at Pazhani, Dindigul and Chennai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/52132.html |title=Arun Vijay injured at \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 shoot&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> The title song of the film was shot in Pondicherry schedule with 80 junior artists. Few stunts were shot at Trichy and Stunt master Kanal Kannan has given 45 days of his schedule.<ref name=\"indiaglitz1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/52924.html |title=\u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 moves to Trichy&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nBefore the release, Dr. Kalidoss has stated that he had been in the film industry for the past 15 years and that he completed a film titled \u2018Thunichal\u2019 with Arun Vijay in the lead in the year 2008. He also stated that though the Censor Board had cleared the film, Arun Vijay had \u2018purposely\u2019 delayed the release of the film by not completing his portion of the \u2018dubbing\u2019 work. As he had spent Rs.2 crores till date, the producer told Vijay that he couldn\u2019t continue to shoot the film. Meanwhile, he was asked by the actor to release Thunichal after his \u2018Malai Malai\u2019 released. Due to his non-cooperation, instead of releasing \u2018Thunichal\u2019 in 160 theatres, I could release the film only in 16 theatres on 1 January this year, said Kalidoss. Due to this, I incurred a loss of Rs.1.5 crores, he added. \"Due to the mental harassment I had to endure because of Arun Vijay, I couldn\u2019t continue my profession as a doctor for the past 4 years. Vijay has to pay me Rs.1.5 crores and till he does so, the release of his \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 should be stayed till the 19th of this month,\" he had stated in the petition<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/arun-vijay-s-maanja-velu-is-stayed-by-hc.htm |title=Arun Vijay's 'Maanja Velu' is stayed by HC&#124;Maanja Velu Film&#124;Movies |publisher=Movies.sulekha.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> \nDr. Mohan, producer of \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 and father-in-law of Arun Vijay, had filed a counter petition with the Court praying for vacation of the stay on the grounds that he, as a producer, had nothing to do with Dr. Kalidoss\u2019 case and requested that as such, his film should be allowed to release on the stipulated date. Advocate G. Murugesh Kumar, who appeared on behalf of Dr. Mohan in the court of Mr. Justice T.S. Sivagnanam, managed to putforth his point of view strongly before the Judge and said that Dr. Kalidoss had \u2018wrongly informed\u2019 the Court in the matter. As soon as the Judge announced that he\u2019d be giving the verdict based on the \u2018actual nature\u2019 of the case, Dr. Kalidoss is said to have \u2018withdrawn\u2019 his petition from the Court. Following this, the Judge dismissed the petition and said that the film could release on 21 May as per its original schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.sulekha.com/tamil/maanja-velu/news/high-court-clears-hurdles-in-release-of-maanja-velu.htm |title=High Court clears hurdles in release of 'Maanja Velu'&#124;Maanja Velu Film&#124;Movies |publisher=Movies.sulekha.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Maanja Velu\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Mani Sharma]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Front Cover\n| released   =\n| recorded   = Gemini Music\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Junglee Music\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe soundtrack is composed by [[Mani Sharma]] and he reused the tunes from the original film ''[[Lakshyam (2007 film)|Lakshyam]]''. Audio function was attended by Producers Council chief Rama Narayanan, secretary Sivasakthi pandian, director Shakthi Chidambaram, actors [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]], [[Shaam (actor)|Shaam]], [[Jai (actor)|Jai]], [[Sibiraj]], [[Sundar C.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/55267.html |title=\u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 marks his presence&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Performer(s)\n| title1 = Munneru Munneru\n| extra1 = [[Ranjith (singer)|Ranjith]], Naveen\n| lyrics1 = [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]]\n| title2 = Eppadi Thaan Muraichu\n| extra2 = [[Rahul Nambiar]]\n| lyrics2 = Vaali\n| title3 = Maanja Maanja\n| extra3 = [[Tippu (singer)|Tippu]], [[Sujatha Mohan|Sujatha]]\n| lyrics3 = Vaali\n| title4 = Oh My Dear\n| extra4 = Ranjith, [[Saindhavi]]\n| lyrics4 = [[Viveka (lyricist)|Viveka]]\n| title5 = Ooril Ulla Uyirghalelaam\n| extra5 = [[Karthik (singer)|Karthik]]\n| lyrics5 = Vaali\n| title6 = Maanja Maanja\n| note6  = Retro Remix\n| extra6 = Mukesh, Priya Subramaniam\n| lyrics6 = Vaali\n}}\n\n===Critical response===\nThe soundtrack was released to generally positive reviews. Behindwoods said, \"there is nothing in the album that will make it stand up for itself\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-music-reviews/review-1/maanja-velu-arun-vijay.html |title=Maanja Velu&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Music Reviews |publisher=Behindwoods |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Milliblog said, \"getting 3 decent tracks in a masala potboiler soundtrack is a huge win indeed\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://itwofs.com/milliblog/2010/03/16/music-review-maanja-velu-tamil-manisharma/ |title=Music review: Maanja Velu (Tamil&nbsp;\u2013 Manisharma) by Milliblog! |publisher=Itwofs.com |date=2010-03-16 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Indiaglitz said, \"Over all, the music of Maanja Velu will definitely be chart busters and the music will have a wide reach. Mani Sharma, has used the tunes of his hit songs in Telugu in this album, which would surely appeal even to the Tamil audience\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/musicreview/11477.html |title=Maanja Velu Music Review songs lyrics |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date=2010-03-13 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe satellite rights of the film were sold to [[Kalaignar TV|Kalaignar]]. The film was given an \"A\" certificate by the [[Indian Censor Board]] and released on 21 May 2010 alongside ''[[Magane En Marumagane]]'', ''[[Kanakavel Kaaka]]'', ''[[Kutti Pisasu]]'', ''[[Kola Kolaya Mundhirika]]'' and ''[[Police Police|Kutrapirivu]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/movies/More-movies-in-May-news-tamil-kkfqA0cjijf.html |title=More movies in May|publisher=Sify |date=2010-05-04 |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref>\n\n===Reviews===\nSify said, \"On the whole director Venkatesh has dished out an average run of the mill mass masala cocktail which is quite entertaining in the first half but fizzles out in the second half with a predictable long drawn out climax\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/maanja-velu-review-tamil-14942723.html |title=Movie Review:Maanja Velu|publisher=Sify |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Behindwoods said, \"Maanja Velu is an entertainer that aims to satisfy all types of audiences and A. Venkatesh has managed to create a screenplay that takes care of all requirements. But, there is a feeling that the full potential of the script has not been realized. It is still a decent entertainer which can be watched especially for its wonderful casting\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-reviews/reviews-2/maanja-velu-arun-vijay-prabhu.html |title=Maanja Velu&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie Reviews |publisher=Behindwoods |date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Times of India said, \"The one thing that strikes you about Maanja Velu is what a talent house Tamil cinema has been. As you watch the parade of the seniors like Karthik, Prabhu, Vijaykumar and Vagai Chandrasekhar you feel glad that they came up with good, great, moving or simply lovable performances in the past. It does a lot to ease the heart burn caused by the so-called earthy cinema that we have been treated to for months and months now. Where you saw plenty of victims of circumstances on display, but so very lacking in angst that you came away from the movie without any emotional connect\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/tamil/Maanja-Velu/movie-review/5968741.cms |title=Maanja Velu movie review|publisher=The Times of India|date= |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Indiaglitz said, \"A perfect one for those who love masala flicks\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/review/11477.html |title=Maanja Velu Tamil Movie Review |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date=2010-05-22 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Chennaionline said, \"Maanja Velu has all the ingredients of a masala flick but the problem is that it has no novelty or neatness to impress us\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chennaionline.com/movies/movie-reviews/20102527102500/Movie-Review-Maanja-Velu.col |title=Movie Review: \u2018Maanja Velu\u2019 |publisher=ChennaiOnline |date=2010-05-27 |accessdate=2012-06-01}}</ref> Top 10 cinema said, \"The movie may have its reach amongst the commercial film lovers, who have no regards for logics\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.top10cinema.com/review/4680/maanja-velu |title=Maanja Velu &#124; Movie Review |publisher=Top 10 Cinema |date=2010-05-24 |accessdate=2012-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527100635/http://www.top10cinema.com/review/4680/maanja-velu |archivedate=27 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Box Office===\nThe film has seen an above average opening with total collections running up to Rs. 18 lakhs and weekend collections at Rs. 3,38,177 in second week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://600024.com/specials/chennai-box-office-collections-%e2%80%93-may-28-30/9/ |title=Special \u00bb Chennai Box Office Collections&nbsp;\u2013 May 28\u201330 |publisher=600024.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref> After that, weekend saw Rs. 4,22,307 drawn in its favor with Rs. 26 lakhs over the last weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://600024.com/specials/chennai-box-office-collections-june-04-06/5/ |title=Special \u00bb Chennai Box Office Collections June 04\u201306 |publisher=600024.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref> Rs. 1,76,967 was made by the film this weekend with Rs. 32 lakhs spanning over 3 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://600024.com/specials/chennai-box-office-collections-june-11-to-13/3/ |title=Special \u00bb Chennai Box Office Collections June 11 to 13 |publisher=600024.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref> Total collections in Chennai was Rs. 26 lakhs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-slide-shows/movie-4/top-ten-movies-june-07/tamil-cinema-topten-movie-maanja-velu.html |title=Maanja Velu&nbsp;\u2014 Behindwoods.com&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Top Ten Movies&nbsp;\u2014 Maanja Velu Singam Sura Goripalayam Kanagavel Kakka |publisher=Behindwoods |date= |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref> Overall trade pundits declared the film as \"decent hit\" due to the medium budget it was produced on.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=4316170}}\n\n{{A. Venkatesh (director)}}\n\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Tamil remakes of Telugu films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tiruchirappalli]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:2010s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Tamil film scores by Mani Sharma]]\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Masala films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tiruchirappalli]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Tamil Nadu Police]]\n[[Category:Indian nonlinear narrative films]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: couldn\u2019t \u2192 couldn't, he\u2019d \u2192 he'd, \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maanja_Velu"}
{"title_page": "Open defecation", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]; [[WP:RFPP]] request|small=yes}}\n\n{{short description|Humans defecating outside (in the open environment) rather than into a toilet}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n\n'''Open defecation''' is the human practice of [[defecating]] outside (in the open environment) rather than into a [[toilet]]. People may choose fields, bushes, forests, ditches, streets, canals or other open space for defecation. They do so because either they do not have a toilet readily accessible or due to traditional cultural practices.<ref name=\"ClasenBoisson2014\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Clasen T, Boisson S, Routray P, Torondel B, Bell M, Cumming O, Ensink J, Freeman M, Jenkins M, Odagiri M, Ray S, Sinha A, Suar M, Schmidt WP | display-authors = 6 | title = Effectiveness of a rural sanitation programme on diarrhoea, soil-transmitted helminth infection, and child malnutrition in Odisha, India: a cluster-randomised trial | journal = The Lancet. Global Health | volume = 2 | issue = 11 | pages = e645-53 | date = November 2014 | pmid = 25442689 | doi = 10.1016/S2214-109X(14)70307-9 }}</ref> The practice is common where [[sanitation]] infrastructure and services are not available. Even if toilets are available, [[Behavior change (public health)|behavior change]] efforts may still be needed to promote the use of toilets.\n\n'''Open defecation free''' (ODF) is used to describe communities that have shifted to using a toilet instead of open defecation. This can happen for example after [[community-led total sanitation]] programs have been implemented.\n\nThe current estimate is that around 673 million people practise open defecation.<ref name=\"JMP2019\">WHO and UNICEF (2019) [https://www.who.int/water_sanitation_health/publications/jmp-report-2019/en/ Progress on household drinking water, sanitation and hygiene 2000\u20132017: Special focus on inequalities], Geneva, Switzerland</ref>{{rp|74}} This is down from about 892 million people, or 12 percent of the global population, who practiced open defecation in 2016.<ref name=\"JMP2017\" /> In that year, seventy-six percent (678 million) of the 892 million people practicing open defecation in the world live in just seven countries.<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />\n\nOpen defecation can pollute the environment and cause health problems. High levels of open defecation are linked to high [[child mortality]], poor [[undernutrition|nutrition]], [[poverty]], and large disparities between rich and poor.<ref name=\"JMP2014\">{{cite book|url=http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/2036|title=Progress on drinking water and sanitation, 2014 Update|date=2014|publisher=WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation (JMP)|isbn=9789241507240}}</ref>{{rp|page=11}}\n\nEnding open defecation is an indicator being used to measure progress towards the [[Sustainable Development Goal 6|Sustainable Development Goal Number 6]]. Extreme poverty and lack of sanitation are statistically linked. Therefore, eliminating open defecation is thought to be an important part of the effort to eliminate poverty.<ref name=\"Ahmad\">{{cite news|url=https://www.devex.com/news/how-to-eliminate-open-defecation-by-2030-84634|title=How to eliminate open defecation by 2030| vauthors = Ahmad J |date=30 October 2014|access-date=2 May 2016|website=devex}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Background ==\n\nDefecating in the open is a very ancient practice. In ancient times, there were more open spaces and less population pressure on land. It was believed that defecating in the open causes little harm when done in areas with low population, forests, or camping type situations. With development and urbanization, open defecating started becoming a challenge and thereby an important [[public health]] issue, and an issue of human [[dignity]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=O'Reilly |first=Kathleen | name-list-format = vanc |date=2016-01-01|title=From toilet insecurity to toilet security: creating safe sanitation for women and girls|journal=Wiley Interdisciplinary Reviews: Water|language=en|volume=3|issue=1|pages=19\u201324|doi=10.1002/wat2.1122|issn=2049-1948}}</ref> With the increase in population in smaller areas, such as cities and towns, more attention was given to hygiene and health. As a result, there was an increase in global attention towards reducing the practice of open defecation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/2017/08/toilet-defecate-outdoors-stunting-sanitation/|title=Nearly a Billion People Still Defecate Outdoors. Here's Why.|date=2017-07-25|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n\nOpen defecation perpetuates the vicious cycle of disease and poverty and is widely regarded as an affront to personal dignity.<ref name=\"JMP2014\" /> The countries where open defecation is most widely practised have the highest numbers of [[Child mortality|deaths of children]] under the age of five, as well as high levels of [[Malnutrition|undernutrition]], high levels of poverty, and large disparities between the rich and poor.<ref name=\"JMP2014\" />\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Waste dumping in a slum of Cap-Haitien.jpg|Indiscriminate waste dumping and open defecation, Shadda, [[Cap-Haitien]], Haiti\nFile:Open defecation in Tirin Kowt bazaar (4361881653).jpg|Open defecation, Tirin Kowt bazaar, [[Afghanistan]]\nFile:Open defecation along the river bank (6908382463).jpg|Open defecation along a river bank in [[Bujumbura]], Burundi\nFile:Child in open sewer in Nigeria (3150664698).jpg|Child defecating in the open in a canal in the slum of Gege in the city of [[Ibadan]], Nigeria\nFile:Drain? Or Toilet? (3683494818).jpg|This drain is used to defecate and urinate in a community in Bangladesh\n</gallery>\n\n== Terminology ==\n\nThe term \"open defecation\" became widely used in the water, sanitation, and hygiene ([[WASH]]) sector from about 2008 onwards. This was due to the publications by the [[Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation]] (JMP) and the UN [[International Year of Sanitation]]. The JMP is a joint program by [[World Health Organization|WHO]] and [[UNICEF]] to monitor the water and sanitation targets of the [[Sustainable Development Goal 6|Sustainable Development Goal Number 6]].\n\nFor monitoring purposes, two categories were created: 1) [[improved sanitation]] and (2) [[unimproved sanitation]]. Open defecation falls into the category of unimproved sanitation. This means that people who practice open defecation do not have access to improved sanitation.\n\nIn 2013 [[World Toilet Day]] was celebrated as an official UN day for the first time. The term \"open defecation\" was used in high-level speeches, that helped to draw global attention to this issue (for example, in the \"call to action\" on sanitation issued by the Deputy Secretary-General of the United Nations in March 2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/millenniumgoals/pdf/DSG%20sanitation%20two-pager%20FINAL.pdf|title=United Nations Deputy Secretary-General's Call to Action on Sanitation|date=2013|website=United Nations|access-date=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Open defecation free ===\n\n\"Open defecation free\" (ODF) is a phrase first used in [[community-led total sanitation]] (CLTS) programs. ODF has now entered use in other contexts. The original meaning of ODF stated that all community members are using sanitation facilities (such as toilets) instead of going to the open for defecation. This definition was improved and more criteria were added in some countries that have adopted the CLTS approach in their programs to stop the practice of open defecation.<ref name=\"Cavill\">{{cite book |url= http://www.communityledtotalsanitation.org/resource/frontiers-clts-issue-4-sustainability-and-clts-taking-stock |title=Sustainability and CLTS: Taking Stock Frontiers of CLTS: Innovations and Insights Issue 4 |last1=Cavill |last2=Chambers |last3=Vernon | name-list-format = vanc |date=2015 |publisher=IDS |isbn=978-1-78118-222-2 |page=18 }}</ref>\n\nThe Indian [[Ministry of Drinking Water and Sanitation]] has in mid-2015 defined ODF as \"the termination of [[fecal-oral transmission]], defined by:\n\n# No visible feces found in the environment or village and\n# Every household as well as public/community institutions using safe technology option for disposal of feces\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdws.gov.in/sites/default/files/R_274_1441280478318.pdf|title=Guidelines for ODF Verification|date=2015|publisher=Indian Ministry of Drinking Water and Sanitation}}</ref>\n\nHere, 'safe technology option' means toilets that contain feces so that there is no contamination of surface soil, groundwater or surface water; flies or animals do not come in contact with the open feces; no one handles excreta; there is no smell and there are no visible feces around in the environment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://forum.susana.org/71-behaviour-change-and-user-psychology-issues/13746-definition-of-odf-open-defecation-free-indian-government-publication|title=Definition of ODF \u2013 Open Defecation Free (Indian government publication)|date=2015-06-18|access-date=2017-10-05|language=en-gb}}</ref> This definition is part of the [[Swachh Bharat Abhiyan]] (Clean India Campaign).\n\n== Reasons ==\n\nThe reasons for open defecation are varied. It can be a voluntary, semi-voluntary or involuntary choice. Most of the time, a lack of access to a toilet is the reason. However, in some places even people with toilets in their houses prefer to defecate in the open.<ref name=\"Cavill\" />\n\nA few broad factors that result in the practice of open defecation are listed below.\n\n=== No toilet ===\n\n* Lack of infrastructure: People often lack toilets in their houses, or in the areas where they live.<ref name=\"JMP2019\" /><ref name=\"Routray 880\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Routray P, Schmidt WP, Boisson S, Clasen T, Jenkins MW | title = Socio-cultural and behavioural factors constraining latrine adoption in rural coastal Odisha: an exploratory qualitative study | journal = BMC Public Health | volume = 15 | pages = 880 | date = September 2015 | pmid = 26357958 | pmc = 4566293 | doi = 10.1186/s12889-015-2206-3 }}</ref>\n* Lack of toilets in other places: Lack of toilets in places away from people's houses, such as in schools or in the farms lead the people to defecate in the open.<ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* Use of toilets for other purposes: In some rural communities, toilets are used for other purposes, such as storing household items, animals, farm products or used as kitchens. In such cases, people go outside to defecate.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bardosh|first=Kevin | name-list-format = vanc |date=2015-11-01|title=Achieving \"Total Sanitation\" in Rural African Geographies: Poverty, Participation and Pit Latrines in Eastern Zambia|journal=Geoforum|volume=66|issue=Supplement C|pages=53\u201363|doi=10.1016/j.geoforum.2015.09.004}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/2762|title=Understanding Gendered Sanitation Vulnerabilities: A Study in Uttar Pradesh - Resources \u2022 SuSanA|website=www.susana.org|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref> Another example is a lack of [[public toilets]] in cities, which can be a big problem for [[Homelessness|homeless people]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2017/04/03/public-bathrooms-opioids|title=Public Bathrooms Become Ground Zero In The Opioid Epidemic|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Uncomfortable or unsafe toilet ===\n\n* Poor quality of toilet: Sometimes people have access to a toilet, but the toilet might be broken, or of poor quality \u2013 Outdoor toilets (pit latrines in particular) typically are devoid of any type of cleaning and reek of odors. Sometimes, toilets are not well lit, especially in areas that lack electricity. Others lack doors or may not have water. Toilets with maggots or cockroaches are also disliked by people and hence, they go out to defecate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wsp.org/sites/wsp.org/files/publications/WSP-What-Influences-Open-Defecation-Global-Sanitation-Review.pdf|title=What Influences Open Defecation and Latrine Ownership in Rural Households?: Findings from a Global Review |last=O'Connell |first=Kathryn | name-list-format = vanc |date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wateraid.org/se/~/media/Files/Sweden/nowhere-to-go.pdf|title=Nowhere to go How a lack of safe toilets threatens to increase violence against women in slums|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611225519/http://www.wateraid.org/se/%7E/media/Files/Sweden/nowhere%2Dto%2Dgo.pdf|archive-date=2014-06-11|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kwiringira J, Atekyereza P, Niwagaba C, G\u00fcnther I | title = Descending the sanitation ladder in urban Uganda: evidence from Kampala Slums | journal = BMC Public Health | volume = 14 | pages = 624 | date = June 2014 | pmid = 24948084 | pmc = 4071028 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2458-14-624 }}</ref><ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* Risky and unsafe: Some toilets are risky to access. There may be a risk to personal safety due to lack of lights at night, criminals around them, or the presence of animals such as snakes and dogs. Women and children who do not have toilets inside their houses are often found to be scared to access shared or public toilets, especially at night.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/AFR32/002/2010/en/|title=Document|website=www.amnesty.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref> Accessing toilets that are not located in the house might be a problem for disabled people, especially at night.<ref name=\"Tsinda 6939\u20136954\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tsinda A, Abbott P, Pedley S, Charles K, Adogo J, Okurut K, Chenoweth J | title = Challenges to achieving sustainable sanitation in informal settlements of Kigali, Rwanda | journal = International Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health | volume = 10 | issue = 12 | pages = 6939\u201354 | date = December 2013 | pmid = 24336021 | pmc = 3881150 | doi = 10.3390/ijerph10126939 }}</ref>\n* Presence of toilet but not privacy: Some toilets do not have a real door, but have a cloth hung as a door. In some communities, toilets are located in places where women are shy to access them due to the presence of men.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=O'Reilly |first=Kathleen| name-list-format = vanc |date=2006-11-01|title=\"Traditional\" women, \"modern\" water: Linking gender and commodification in Rajasthan, India|journal=Geoforum|volume=37|issue=6|pages=958\u2013972|doi=10.1016/j.geoforum.2006.05.008}}</ref><ref name=\"Tsinda 6939\u20136954\" /><ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* Lack of water near toilet: Absence of supply of water inside or next to toilets cause people to get water from a distance before using the toilet.<ref name=\"Routray 880\" /> This is an additional task and needs extra time.\n* Too many people using a toilet: This is especially true in case of shared or public toilets. If too many people want to use a toilet at the same time, then some people may go outside to defecate instead of waiting. In some cases, people might not be able to wait due to diarrhea (or result of an Irritable Bowel Syndrome emergency).\n* Fear of the pit getting filled: In some places, people are scared that their toilet pits will get filled very fast if all family members use it everyday. So they continue to go out to delay the toilet pit filling up. This is especially true in the case of a pit latrine.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Tsinda 6939\u20136954\" />\n\n=== Unrelated to toilet infrastructure ===\n\n* Lack of awareness: People in some communities do not know about the benefits of using toilets.<ref>In 2016, Kunwar Bai Yadav, a woman claiming to be 105 years old, said she had never heard about a toilet until that year, and had always gone into the nearby woods to defecate. Only when she learned about them, did she have one built in her community. Source: BBC News (India): [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-37799425 \"How a 105-year-old ended open defecation in her village\"], 1 November 2016</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://riceinstitute.org/research/revealed-preference-for-open-defecation-evidence-from-a-new-survey-in-rural-north-india-longer-working-paper/|title=Revealed Preference for Open Defecation: Evidence from a new survey in rural north India (longer working paper) {{!}} r.i.c.e.|website=riceinstitute.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref>\n* Lack of [[Behavior change (public health)|behavior change]]: Some communities have toilets, yet people prefer to defecate in the open.<ref name=\"Cavill\" /> In some cases, these toilets are provided by the government or other organizations and the people do not like them, or do not value them. They continue to defecate in the open. Also, older people are often found to defecate in the open and they are hesitant to change their behavior and go inside a closed toilet.<ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* Prefer being in nature: This happens mostly in less populated or rural areas, where people walk outside early in the morning and go to defecate in the fields or bushes. They prefer to be in nature and the fresh air; instead of defecating in a closed space such as a toilet.<ref name=\"Ahmad\" /> There may be cultural or habitual preference for defecating \"in the open air\", beside a local river or stream, or even the bush.\n* Combining open defecation with other activities: Some people walk early in the morning to look after their farms. Some consider it as a social activity, especially women who like to take some time to go out of their homes. While on their way to the fields for open defecation they can talk to other women and take care of their animals.<ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* [[Norm (social)|Social norms]]: Open defecation is a part of people's life and daily habit in some regions (e.g. in India). It is an ancient practice and is hard for many people to stop practicing. It is a part of a routine or social norm. In some cultures, there may be social taboos where a father-in-law may not use the same toilet as daughter-in-law in the same household.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n* [[Fecal incontinence]]: This medical condition can result in abrupt 'emergencies' and not enough time to access a toilet.\n\n=== Public defecation for other reasons ===\n\nIn [[Developed country|developed countries]], open defecation is either due to [[homelessness]], or considered to be a part of voluntary, recreational outdoor activities in remote areas. It is difficult to estimate how many people practice open defecation in these communities.\n\n[[The Mad Pooper]] is the name given to an unidentified woman who regularly defecated in public places while jogging during summer 2017 in the U.S. city of [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]].\n\n== Prevalence and trends ==\n\nThe practice of open defecation is s [[Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation|and Sanitation]] (JMP) of UNICEF and WHO has been collecting data regarding open defecation prevalence worldwide. The figures are segregated by rural and urban areas and by levels of poverty. This program is tasked to monitor progress towards the millennium development goal (MDG) relating to drinking water and sanitation. As open defecation is one example of [[unimproved sanitation]], it is being monitored by JMP for each country and results published on a regular basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.wssinfo.org/data-estimates/|title = Data and estimates|access-date = 12 March 2015|website = JMP \u2013 WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply and Sanitation|publisher = WHO/UNICEF|url-status = dead|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150219114756/http://www.wssinfo.org/data-estimates|archive-date = 19 February 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"JMP2017\">WHO and UNICEF (2017) [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/2805 Progress on Drinking Water, Sanitation and Hygiene: 2017 Update and SDG Baselines]. Geneva: World Health Organization (WHO) and the United Nations Children\u2019s Fund (UNICEF)</ref> The figures on open defecation used to be lumped together with other figures on unimproved sanitation but are collected separately since 2010.\n\nThe current estimate is that  around 673 million people practise open defecation.<ref name=\"JMP2019\"/>{{rp|74}}\n\nIn San Francisco (United States), open defecation complaints for street feces increased fivefold from 2011 to 2018, with 28,084 cases reported.<ref>{{cite web | title = San Francisco plans to power-wash the poop out of the Tenderloin | url = https://www.sfgate.com/local/article/City-plans-to-power-wash-the-poop-out-of-the-14878629.php | first = Mike | last = Moffitt | name-list-format = vanc | work = SFGATE | date = 3 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe number of people practicing open defecation fell from 20 percent in 2000 to 12 percent in 2015.<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />{{rp|page=34}} In 2016, the estimate was for 892 million people with no sanitation facility whatsoever and therefore practising open defecation (in gutters, behind bushes, in open water bodies etc.). Most people (9 of 10) who practice open defecation live in rural areas, but the vast majority lives in two regions ([[Central Asia]] and [[South Asia]]).<ref name=\"JMP2017\" /> In 2016, seventy-six percent (678 million) of the 892 million people practicing open defecation in the world lived in just seven countries.<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />\n\nThe countries with large numbers of people who openly defecate are listed in the table below.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+People practicing open defecation by country \u2013 in alphabetical order (use up and down arrows to order by numbers). The figures in column 2 and 3 are from 2015, as reported in 2017 by [[Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation|JMP]]<ref name=\"JMP2017\" /> and made accessible on several websites<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SH.STA.ODFC.ZS|title=People practicing open defecation (% of population)|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Country\n!Total country population (in thousands) in 2015 as reported in 2017 by JMP<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | Percentage of people who defecate in the open and absolute numbers (data from 2015 as reported in 2017 by JMP<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />)\n!More recent estimates of people defecating in the open (not JMP data but government data)\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Chad]]\n| 14,037\n| 68% Or 10 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | China\n| 1,376,049\n| 2% Or 28 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Eritrea]]\n| 5,228\n| 76% Or 4 million\n|\n|- Class=\"sortbottom\"\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Ethiopia\n| 99,391\n| 27% Or 27 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | India\n| 1,311,051\n| 39.84% Or 524 million\n| Developments since 2017:\n\n* 6.6% Or 88 millions in 2018 according to NRASS conducted by Independent Verificatiom Agency (IVA) of World Bank<ref>{{Cite News|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=178030|title=Independent Verification of Swachh Bharat Gramin confirms 93% usage of toilets|date = 27 March 2018|access-date = 11 March 2019|newspaper = Press Information Bureau}}</ref>\n* 1.4% Or 19 million in January 2019<br>according to government data<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|title = Swachh Bharat Mission \u2013 Gramin|url = http://swachhbharatmission.gov.in/sbmcms/index.htm|access-date = 15 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uniindia.com/over-83-9-million-toilets-constructed-under-swachh-bharat-mission/india/news/1350692.html|title=Over 83 9 million toilets constructed under Swachh Bharat Mission|access-date=14 September 2018|publisher=UNI India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/blogs/the-needles-eye/cleaning-up-india-with-gandhiji/|title=Cleaning Up India With Gandhiji|access-date=20 September 2018|publisher=Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Indonesia\n| 257,564\n| 12% Or 31 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Niger\n| 19,899\n| 71% Or 14 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Nigeria\n| 182,202\n| 26% Or 47 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Pakistan\n| 188,925\n| 12% Or 23 million\n|\n* 11.5% Or 21.8 million in 2015 as per WaterAid report<ref>{{Cite news|title = 79m Pakistanis still lack a decent toilet: report|url = https://dailytimes.com.pk/145728/79m-pakistanis-still-lack-decent-toilet-report/|date = November 23, 2017|access-date = September 21, 2019|newspaper = [[Daily Times (Pakistan)]]}}</ref>\n* 21.7% Or 41 million in 2015 as per UNICEF<ref>{{Cite news|title = Pakistan among 10 worst countries for access to toilets|url = https://www.dawn.com/news/1168181|date = March 8, 2015|access-date = September 21, 2019|newspaper = [[Dawn (newspaper)|The Dawn]]}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[South Sudan]]\n| 12,340\n| 61% Or 8 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Sudan\n| 40,235\n| 27% Or 11 million\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n== Impacts ==\n\n[[File:Dirty pit latrine in Mongolia in winter (5321157342).jpg|thumb|upright|A dirty pit latrine in Mongolia leading people to choose open defecation instead]]\n\n=== Public health ===\n{{Further|Sanitation#Health_aspects}}\n\nThe negative [[public health]] impacts of open defecation are the same as those described when there is no access to [[sanitation]] at all. Open defecation\u2014and lack of [[sanitation]] and [[hygiene]] in general\u2014is an important factor that cause various diseases; the most common being [[infectious diarrhea|diarrhea]] and [[helminthiasis|intestinal worm infections]] but also [[typhoid]], [[cholera]], [[hepatitis]], [[polio]], [[trachoma]], and others.<ref name=\"UN2015\">{{cite web|title=Call to action on sanitation|url=http://sanitationdrive2015.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSG_Sanitation_Fast-Facts_final.pdf|website=United Nations|access-date=15 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ChaturvediSpears2013\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Spears D, Ghosh A, Cumming O | title = Open defecation and childhood stunting in India: an ecological analysis of new data from 112 districts | journal = PloS One | volume = 8 | issue = 9 | pages = e73784 | year = 2013 | pmid = 24066070 | pmc = 3774764 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0073784 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, infectious diarrhea resulted in about 0.7 million deaths in children under five years old and 250 million lost school days.<ref name=\"UN2015\" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Walker CL, Rudan I, Liu L, Nair H, Theodoratou E, Bhutta ZA, O'Brien KL, Campbell H, Black RE | display-authors = 6 | title = Global burden of childhood pneumonia and diarrhoea | journal = Lancet | volume = 381 | issue = 9875 | pages = 1405\u20131416 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23582727 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(13)60222-6 }}</ref> It can also lead to [[Undernutrition in children|malnutrition]] and [[stunted growth]] among children.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Spears D, Ghosh A, Cumming O | title = Open defecation and childhood stunting in India: an ecological analysis of new data from 112 districts | journal = PloS One | volume = 8 | issue = 9 | pages = e73784 | date = 2013-09-16 | pmid = 24066070 | pmc = 3774764 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0073784 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mara|first=Duncan | name-list-format = vanc |date=2017-03-01|title=The elimination of open defecation and its adverse health effects: a moral imperative for governments and development professionals|url=http://washdev.iwaponline.com/content/7/1/1|journal=Journal of Water Sanitation and Hygiene for Development|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=1\u201312|doi=10.2166/washdev.2017.027|issn=2043-9083}}</ref>\n\nCertain diseases are grouped together under the name of [[waterborne diseases]], which are diseases transmitted via fecal pathogens in water. Open defecation can lead to [[water pollution]] when rain flushes feces that are dispersed in the environment into [[surface water]] or unprotected [[water well|wells]].\n\nOpen defecation was found by the [[WHO]] in 2014 to be a leading cause of diarrheal death. An average of 2,000 children under the age of five die every day from diarrhea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs330/en/ |title=WHO &#124; Diarrhoeal disease |publisher=World Health Organization |date=2013 |access-date=10 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nYoung children are particularly vulnerable to ingesting feces of other people that are lying around after open defecation, because young children crawl on the ground, walk barefoot, and put things in their mouths without washing their hands. Feces of farm animals are equally a cause of concern when children are playing in the yard.\n\nThose countries where open defecation is most widely practiced have the highest numbers of deaths of children under the age of five, as well as high levels of malnourishment (leading to [[stunted growth]] in children), high levels of poverty and large disparities between rich and poor.<ref name=\"JMP2014\" />\n\nResearch from India has shown that detrimental health impacts (particularly for early life health) are even more significant from open defecation when the population density is high: \"The same amount of open defecation is twice as bad in a place with a high population density average like India versus a low population density average like sub-Saharan Africa.\"<ref>{{cite book| last1=Vyas|date=2014| url=http://www.susana.org/_resources/documents/default/3-2089-16-1414062223.pdf|title=Population density and the effect of sanitation on early-life health], slide 19 (presentation at UNC conference in Oct. 2014)|publisher= Research Institute for Compassionate Economics, project (r.i.c.e.)}}</ref>\n\n=== Safety of women ===\n\nThere are strong gender impacts connected with open defecation. The lack of safe, private toilets makes women and girls vulnerable to violence and is an impediment to girls' education.<ref name=\":1\" /> Women are at risk of sexual molestation and rape as they search for places for open defecation that are secluded and private, often during hours of darkness.<ref>Lennon, S. (2011). [http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1758 Fear and anger: Perceptions of risks related to sexual violence against women linked to water and sanitation in Delhi, India] \u2013 Briefing Note. SHARE (Sanitation and Hygiene Applied Research for Equity) and WaterAid, UK </ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite book | last1 = House | first1 = Sarah | first2 = Suzanne | last2 = Ferron | first3 = Marni | last3 = Sommer | first4 = Sue | last4 = Cavill | name-list-format = vanc | date = 2014 | url = http://violence-wash.lboro.ac.uk/ | title = Violence, Gender & WASH: A Practitioner\u2019s Toolkit&nbsp;\u2013 Making water, sanitation and hygiene safer through improved programming and services | location = London, UK | publisher = WaterAid/SHARE }}</ref>\n\nLack of [[privacy]] has an especially large effect on the safety and sense of dignity of women and girls in developing countries. They face the shame of having to defecate in public so often wait until nightfall to relieve themselves. They risk being attacked after dark, though it means painfully holding their bladder and bowels all day.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|last1=Cavill|first1=Sue | name-list-format = vanc |title=Violence, gender and WASH: A practitioner's toolkit: Making Water, Sanitation and hygiene safer through improved programming and services|url=http://violence-wash.lboro.ac.uk/|publisher=WaterAid, SHARE Research Consortium|access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite journal|last1=Lennon|first1=Shirley | name-list-format = vanc |title=Fear and anger: Perceptions of risks related to sexual violence against women linked to water and sanitation in Delhi, India|journal=SHARE (Sanitation and Hygiene Applied Research for Equity) and WaterAid, UK|date=November 2011|url=http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1758|access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref> Women in developing countries increasingly express fear of assault or rape when having to leave the house after dark. Reports of attacks or harassment near or in toilet facilities, as well as near or in areas where women defecate openly, are common.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n== Prevention ==\n\nThere are several drivers used to eradicate open defecation, one of which is behaviour change. SaniFOAM (Focus on Opportunity, Ability and Motivation) is a conceptual framework which was developed specifically to address issues of sanitation and hygiene. Using focus, opportunity, ability and motivation as categories of determinants, SaniFOAM model identifies barriers to latrine adoption while simultaneously serving as a tool for designing, monitoring and evaluating sanitation interventions.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Introducing Sanifoam: A Framework to Analyze Sanitation Behaviors to Design Effective Sanitation Programs| vauthors = Devine J |publisher=World Bank|year=2009|isbn=|location=Washington, DC, USA|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| vauthors = Devine J |year=2010|title=Beyond tippt-taps: The role of enabling products in scaling up and sustaining handwashing|url=|journal=Waterlines|volume=29|issue=4|pages=304\u2013314|doi=10.3362/1756-3488.2010.033}}</ref> The following are some of the key drivers used to fight against open defecation in addition to behavior change:<ref name=\"Ahmad\" />\n\n* Political will\n* Sanitation solutions that offer a better value than open defecation\n* Stronger public sector local service delivery systems\n* Creation of the right incentive structures\n\n=== Integrated initiatives ===\n\nEfforts to reduce open defecation are more or less the same as those to achieve the MDG target on access to [[sanitation]]. A key aspect is awareness raising (for example via the UN [[World Toilet Day]] at a global level), behaviour change campaigns, increasing political will as well as demand for sanitation. [[Community-Led Total Sanitation]] (CLTS) campaigns have placed a particular focus on ending open defecation by \"triggering\" the communities themselves into action.<ref name=\"fieldnotes\">{{cite web|title=Field Notes: UNICEF Policy and Programming in Practice|url=http://www.unicef.org/socialpolicy/files/Field_Note_-_Community_Approaches_to_Total_Sanitation.pdf|website=UNICEF|access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2014, UNICEF began a multimedia campaign against open defecation in India, urging citizens to \"[[Poo2Loo|take their poo to the loo]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poo2loo.com/ |title=Why take poo to the loo |publisher=Poo2Loo |date= |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Simple sanitation technology options ===\n\n[[File:Photo by Ashley Wheaton, May 2011 (6376606733).jpg|thumb|Residents in [[Mymensingh]], Bangladesh participate in a workshop to discover more about mobile sanitation options (MoSan) as an alternative to open defecation]]\n\nThere are some simple sanitation technology options available to reduce open defecation prevalence if the open defecation behavior is due to not having toilets in the household and shared toilets being too far or too dangerous to reach, e.g., at night.\n\n==== Toilet bags ====\n\nPeople might already use plastic bags (also called [[flying toilet]]s) at night to contain their feces. However, a more advanced solution of the plastic toilet bag has been provided by the Swedish company Peepoople who are producing the \"Peepoo bag\", a \"personal, single-use, self-sanitizing, fully biodegradable toilet that prevents feces from contaminating the immediate area as well as the surrounding ecosystem\".<ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Wheaton A | date = 2009 | url = http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1125 | title = Results of a medium-scale trial of single-use, self-sanitising toilet bags in poor urban settlements in Bangladesh | publisher = Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Technische Zusammenarbeit GmbH (GTZ) | location = Dhaka, Bangladesh }}</ref> This bag is now being used in humanitarian responses, schools, and urban slums in developing countries.<ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Owako E | date = 2012 | url = http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1612 | title = Nyando peepoo trial project report | publisher = Kenya Red Cross | location = Kenya }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Naeem K, Berndtsson M | date = 2011 | url = http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1611 | title = Peepoo Try Pakistan \u2013 Sindh Floods | date = November 2011 | publisher = UN-HABITAT | location = Pakistan }}</ref>\n\n==== Bucket toilets and urine diversion ====\n\n[[Bucket toilet]]s are a simple [[portable toilet]] option. They can be upgraded in various ways, one of them being [[urine diversion]] which can make them similar to [[urine-diverting dry toilet]]s. Urine diversion can significantly reduce odors from [[dry toilet]]s. Examples of using this type of toilet to reduce open defecation are the \"MoSan\"<ref>Mijthab M., Woods E., Lokey H., Foote A., Rieck. C (2013). [http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/2021 Sanivation and MoSan Toilet \u2013 4 week Service Pilot in Karagita Naivasha, Kenya]. GIZ and Sanivation</ref> toilet (used in Kenya) or the urine-diverting dry toilet promoted by [[Sustainable Organic Integrated Livelihoods|SOIL]]<ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Russel K | date = 2013 | url = http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1753 | title = Mobile sanitation services for dense urban slums \u2013 Various documents on results from research grant. | publisher = Stanford University | location = U.S. }}</ref> in Haiti.\n\n=== Media ===\n\nThe mainstream media in some affected countries have recently been picking up on this issue of open defecation, for example, in India<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-29502603 |title=Why India's sanitation crisis needs more than toilets |publisher=[[BBC]] |date= 2014-10-06|access-date=10 March 2015|work=BBC News |last1=Biswas |first1=Soutik | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-india-has-highest-number-of-people-practicing-open-defecation-2036591 |title=India has highest number of people practicing open defecation &#124|publisher=[[DNA India]]|date=19 November 2014 |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref> and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1168181 |title=More than 40m Pakistanis defecate openly: Unicef \u2013 Pakistan |publisher=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |date= 2015-03-08|access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/850024/lack-of-toilets-tied-to-stunted-growth-in-pakistan-unicef/ |title=Lack of toilets tied to stunted growth in Pakistan: UNICEF |publisher=[[Express Tribune]] |date=13 March 2012 |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-6-215001-Over-43-million-people-in-Pakistan-defecate-in-the-open |title=Over 43 million people in Pakistan defecate in the open |publisher=[[The News International]] |date= |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal status ===\n\nIn certain jurisdictions, open or public defecation is a criminal offense which can be punished with a fine or even imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.municode.com/oh/columbus/codes/code_of_ordinances?nodeId=TIT23GEOFCO_CH2317PUCO_2317.14PUURDE|title=Municode Library|website=library.municode.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.columbuscriminalattorney.com/alcohol-offenses/public-urination-defecation/|title=Public Urination/Defecation \u2013 Columbus Criminal Attorney|date=2012-08-13|work=Columbus Criminal Attorney|access-date=2018-01-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wnep.com/2017/09/19/mad-pooper-jogger-wanted-for-repeatedly-defecating-in-colorado-front-yards/|title='Mad Pooper': Jogger Wanted for Defecating in Front Yards of Colorado Homes|date=2017-09-19|work=WNEP.com|access-date=2018-01-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2014/12/01/the-world-is-not-your-toilet-police-note.html|title=The world is NOT your toilet, Columbus police note | last = Allison | first = Manning | name-list-format = vanc |work=The Columbus Dispatch|access-date=2018-01-30 }}</ref>\n\n=== In popular culture ===\n\n[[David Sedaris]]' essay \"Adventures At Poo Corner\" dealt with people who openly defecate in commercial businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/303/david-and-goliath/act-three|title=Adventures At Poo Corner|date=2017-12-12|website=This American Life|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Free Bleeding]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{offline|med}}\n\n* [http://opendefecation.org/news/ UN Call to action to end open defecation]\n* [http://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library?search=open+defecation Documents about open defecation] in library of [[Sustainable Sanitation Alliance]]\n\n{{Toilets}}\n\n{{Pollution}}\n\n{{Public health}}\n\n{{Waste}}\n\n[[Category:Sanitation]]\n[[Category:Defecation]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]; [[WP:RFPP]] request|small=yes}}\n\n{{short description|Humans defecating outside (in the open environment) rather than into a toilet}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n\n'''Open defecation''' is the human practice of [[defecating]] outside (in the open environment) rather than into a [[toilet]]. People may choose fields, bushes, forests, ditches, streets, canals or other open space for defecation. They do so because either they do not have a toilet readily accessible or due to traditional cultural practices.<ref name=\"ClasenBoisson2014\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Clasen T, Boisson S, Routray P, Torondel B, Bell M, Cumming O, Ensink J, Freeman M, Jenkins M, Odagiri M, Ray S, Sinha A, Suar M, Schmidt WP | display-authors = 6 | title = Effectiveness of a rural sanitation programme on diarrhoea, soil-transmitted helminth infection, and child malnutrition in Odisha, India: a cluster-randomised trial | journal = The Lancet. Global Health | volume = 2 | issue = 11 | pages = e645-53 | date = November 2014 | pmid = 25442689 | doi = 10.1016/S2214-109X(14)70307-9 }}</ref> The practice is common where [[sanitation]] infrastructure and services are not available. Even if toilets are available, [[Behavior change (public health)|behavior change]] efforts may still be needed to promote the use of toilets.\n\n'''Open defecation free''' (ODF) is used to describe communities that have shifted to using a toilet instead of open defecation. This can happen for example after [[community-led total sanitation]] programs have been implemented.\n\nThe current estimate is that around 673 million people practise open defecation.<ref name=\"JMP2019\">WHO and UNICEF (2019) [https://www.who.int/water_sanitation_health/publications/jmp-report-2019/en/ Progress on household drinking water, sanitation and hygiene 2000\u20132017: Special focus on inequalities], Geneva, Switzerland</ref>{{rp|74}} This is down from about 892 million people, or 12 percent of the global population, who practiced open defecation in 2016.<ref name=\"JMP2017\" /> In that year, seventy-six percent (678 million) of the 892 million people practicing open defecation in the world live in just seven countries.<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />\n\nOpen defecation can pollute the environment and cause health problems. High levels of open defecation are linked to high [[child mortality]], poor [[undernutrition|nutrition]], [[poverty]], and large disparities between rich and poor.<ref name=\"JMP2014\">{{cite book|url=http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/2036|title=Progress on drinking water and sanitation, 2014 Update|date=2014|publisher=WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation (JMP)|isbn=9789241507240}}</ref>{{rp|page=11}}\n\nEnding open defecation is an indicator being used to measure progress towards the [[Sustainable Development Goal 6|Sustainable Development Goal Number 6]]. Extreme poverty and lack of sanitation are statistically linked. Therefore, eliminating open defecation is thought to be an important part of the effort to eliminate poverty.<ref name=\"Ahmad\">{{cite news|url=https://www.devex.com/news/how-to-eliminate-open-defecation-by-2030-84634|title=How to eliminate open defecation by 2030| vauthors = Ahmad J |date=30 October 2014|access-date=2 May 2016|website=devex}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Background ==\n\nDefecating in the open is a very ancient practice. In ancient times, there were more open spaces and less population pressure on land. It was believed that defecating in the open causes little harm when done in areas with low population, forests, or camping type situations. With development and urbanization, open defecating started becoming a challenge and thereby an important [[public health]] issue, and an issue of human [[dignity]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=O'Reilly |first=Kathleen | name-list-format = vanc |date=2016-01-01|title=From toilet insecurity to toilet security: creating safe sanitation for women and girls|journal=Wiley Interdisciplinary Reviews: Water|language=en|volume=3|issue=1|pages=19\u201324|doi=10.1002/wat2.1122|issn=2049-1948}}</ref> With the increase in population in smaller areas, such as cities and towns, more attention was given to hygiene and health. As a result, there was an increase in global attention towards reducing the practice of open defecation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/2017/08/toilet-defecate-outdoors-stunting-sanitation/|title=Nearly a Billion People Still Defecate Outdoors. Here's Why.|date=2017-07-25|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n\nOpen defecation perpetuates the vicious cycle of disease and poverty and is widely regarded as an affront to personal dignity.<ref name=\"JMP2014\" /> The countries where open defecation is most widely practised have the highest numbers of [[Child mortality|deaths of children]] under the age of five, as well as high levels of [[Malnutrition|undernutrition]], high levels of poverty, and large disparities between the rich and poor.<ref name=\"JMP2014\" />\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Waste dumping in a slum of Cap-Haitien.jpg|Indiscriminate waste dumping and open defecation, Shadda, [[Cap-Haitien]], Haiti\nFile:Open defecation in Tirin Kowt bazaar (4361881653).jpg|Open defecation, Tirin Kowt bazaar, [[Afghanistan]]\nFile:Open defecation along the river bank (6908382463).jpg|Open defecation along a river bank in [[Bujumbura]], Burundi\nFile:Child in open sewer in Nigeria (3150664698).jpg|Child defecating in the open in a canal in the slum of Gege in the city of [[Ibadan]], Nigeria\nFile:Drain? Or Toilet? (3683494818).jpg|This drain is used to defecate and urinate in a community in Bangladesh\n</gallery>\n\n== Terminology ==\n\nThe term \"open defecation\" became widely used in the water, sanitation, and hygiene ([[WASH]]) sector from about 2008 onwards. This was due to the publications by the [[Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation]] (JMP) and the UN [[International Year of Sanitation]]. The JMP is a joint program by [[World Health Organization|WHO]] and [[UNICEF]] to monitor the water and sanitation targets of the [[Sustainable Development Goal 6|Sustainable Development Goal Number 6]].\n\nFor monitoring purposes, two categories were created: 1) [[improved sanitation]] and (2) [[unimproved sanitation]]. Open defecation falls into the category of unimproved sanitation. This means that people who practice open defecation do not have access to improved sanitation.\n\nIn 2013 [[World Toilet Day]] was celebrated as an official UN day for the first time. The term \"open defecation\" was used in high-level speeches, that helped to draw global attention to this issue (for example, in the \"call to action\" on sanitation issued by the Deputy Secretary-General of the United Nations in March 2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/millenniumgoals/pdf/DSG%20sanitation%20two-pager%20FINAL.pdf|title=United Nations Deputy Secretary-General's Call to Action on Sanitation|date=2013|website=United Nations|access-date=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Open defecation free ===\n\n\"Open defecation free\" (ODF) is a phrase first used in [[community-led total sanitation]] (CLTS) programs. ODF has now entered use in other contexts. The original meaning of ODF stated that all community members are using sanitation facilities (such as toilets) instead of going to the open for defecation. This definition was improved and more criteria were added in some countries that have adopted the CLTS approach in their programs to stop the practice of open defecation.<ref name=\"Cavill\">{{cite book |url= http://www.communityledtotalsanitation.org/resource/frontiers-clts-issue-4-sustainability-and-clts-taking-stock |title=Sustainability and CLTS: Taking Stock Frontiers of CLTS: Innovations and Insights Issue 4 |last1=Cavill |last2=Chambers |last3=Vernon | name-list-format = vanc |date=2015 |publisher=IDS |isbn=978-1-78118-222-2 |page=18 }}</ref>\n\nThe Indian [[Ministry of Drinking Water and Sanitation]] has in mid-2015 defined ODF as \"the termination of [[fecal-oral transmission]], defined by:\n\n# No visible feces found in the environment or village and\n# Every household as well as public/community institutions using safe technology option for disposal of feces\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdws.gov.in/sites/default/files/R_274_1441280478318.pdf|title=Guidelines for ODF Verification|date=2015|publisher=Indian Ministry of Drinking Water and Sanitation}}</ref>\n\nHere, 'safe technology option' means toilets that contain feces so that there is no contamination of surface soil, groundwater or surface water; flies or animals do not come in contact with the open feces; no one handles excreta; there is no smell and there are no visible feces around in the environment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://forum.susana.org/71-behaviour-change-and-user-psychology-issues/13746-definition-of-odf-open-defecation-free-indian-government-publication|title=Definition of ODF \u2013 Open Defecation Free (Indian government publication)|date=2015-06-18|access-date=2017-10-05|language=en-gb}}</ref> This definition is part of the [[Swachh Bharat Abhiyan]] (Clean India Campaign).\n\n== Reasons ==\n\nThe reasons for open defecation are varied. It can be a voluntary, semi-voluntary or involuntary choice. Most of the time, a lack of access to a toilet is the reason. However, in some places even people with toilets in their houses prefer to defecate in the open.<ref name=\"Cavill\" />\n\nA few broad factors that result in the practice of open defecation are listed below.\n\n=== No toilet ===\n\n* Lack of infrastructure: People often lack toilets in their houses, or in the areas where they live.<ref name=\"JMP2019\" /><ref name=\"Routray 880\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Routray P, Schmidt WP, Boisson S, Clasen T, Jenkins MW | title = Socio-cultural and behavioural factors constraining latrine adoption in rural coastal Odisha: an exploratory qualitative study | journal = BMC Public Health | volume = 15 | pages = 880 | date = September 2015 | pmid = 26357958 | pmc = 4566293 | doi = 10.1186/s12889-015-2206-3 }}</ref>\n* Lack of toilets in other places: Lack of toilets in places away from people's houses, such as in schools or in the farms lead the people to defecate in the open.<ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* Use of toilets for other purposes: In some rural communities, toilets are used for other purposes, such as storing household items, animals, farm products or used as kitchens. In such cases, people go outside to defecate.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bardosh|first=Kevin | name-list-format = vanc |date=2015-11-01|title=Achieving \"Total Sanitation\" in Rural African Geographies: Poverty, Participation and Pit Latrines in Eastern Zambia|journal=Geoforum|volume=66|issue=Supplement C|pages=53\u201363|doi=10.1016/j.geoforum.2015.09.004}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/2762|title=Understanding Gendered Sanitation Vulnerabilities: A Study in Uttar Pradesh - Resources \u2022 SuSanA|website=www.susana.org|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref> Another example is a lack of [[public toilets]] in cities, which can be a big problem for [[Homelessness|homeless people]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2017/04/03/public-bathrooms-opioids|title=Public Bathrooms Become Ground Zero In The Opioid Epidemic|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Uncomfortable or unsafe toilet ===\n\n* Poor quality of toilet: Sometimes people have access to a toilet, but the toilet might be broken, or of poor quality \u2013 Outdoor toilets (pit latrines in particular) typically are devoid of any type of cleaning and reek of odors. Sometimes, toilets are not well lit, especially in areas that lack electricity. Others lack doors or may not have water. Toilets with maggots or cockroaches are also disliked by people and hence, they go out to defecate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wsp.org/sites/wsp.org/files/publications/WSP-What-Influences-Open-Defecation-Global-Sanitation-Review.pdf|title=What Influences Open Defecation and Latrine Ownership in Rural Households?: Findings from a Global Review |last=O'Connell |first=Kathryn | name-list-format = vanc |date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wateraid.org/se/~/media/Files/Sweden/nowhere-to-go.pdf|title=Nowhere to go How a lack of safe toilets threatens to increase violence against women in slums|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611225519/http://www.wateraid.org/se/%7E/media/Files/Sweden/nowhere%2Dto%2Dgo.pdf|archive-date=2014-06-11|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kwiringira J, Atekyereza P, Niwagaba C, G\u00fcnther I | title = Descending the sanitation ladder in urban Uganda: evidence from Kampala Slums | journal = BMC Public Health | volume = 14 | pages = 624 | date = June 2014 | pmid = 24948084 | pmc = 4071028 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2458-14-624 }}</ref><ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* Risky and unsafe: Some toilets are risky to access. There may be a risk to personal safety due to lack of lights at night, criminals around them, or the presence of animals such as snakes and dogs. Women and children who do not have toilets inside their houses are often found to be scared to access shared or public toilets, especially at night.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/AFR32/002/2010/en/|title=Document|website=www.amnesty.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref> Accessing toilets that are not located in the house might be a problem for disabled people, especially at night.<ref name=\"Tsinda 6939\u20136954\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tsinda A, Abbott P, Pedley S, Charles K, Adogo J, Okurut K, Chenoweth J | title = Challenges to achieving sustainable sanitation in informal settlements of Kigali, Rwanda | journal = International Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health | volume = 10 | issue = 12 | pages = 6939\u201354 | date = December 2013 | pmid = 24336021 | pmc = 3881150 | doi = 10.3390/ijerph10126939 }}</ref>\n* Presence of toilet but not privacy: Some toilets do not have a real door, but have a cloth hung as a door. In some communities, toilets are located in places where women are shy to access them due to the presence of men.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=O'Reilly |first=Kathleen| name-list-format = vanc |date=2006-11-01|title=\"Traditional\" women, \"modern\" water: Linking gender and commodification in Rajasthan, India|journal=Geoforum|volume=37|issue=6|pages=958\u2013972|doi=10.1016/j.geoforum.2006.05.008}}</ref><ref name=\"Tsinda 6939\u20136954\" /><ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* Lack of water near toilet: Absence of supply of water inside or next to toilets cause people to get water from a distance before using the toilet.<ref name=\"Routray 880\" /> This is an additional task and needs extra time.\n* Too many people using a toilet: This is especially true in case of shared or public toilets. If too many people want to use a toilet at the same time, then some people may go outside to defecate instead of waiting. In some cases, people might not be able to wait due to diarrhea (or result of an Irritable Bowel Syndrome emergency).\n* Fear of the pit getting filled: In some places, people are scared that their toilet pits will get filled very fast if all family members use it everyday. So they continue to go out to delay the toilet pit filling up. This is especially true in the case of a pit latrine.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Tsinda 6939\u20136954\" />\n\n=== Unrelated to toilet infrastructure ===\n\n* Lack of awareness: People in some communities do not know about the benefits of using toilets.<ref>In 2016, Kunwar Bai Yadav, a woman claiming to be 105 years old, said she had never heard about a toilet until that year, and had always gone into the nearby woods to defecate. Only when she learned about them, did she have one built in her community. Source: BBC News (India): [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-37799425 \"How a 105-year-old ended open defecation in her village\"], 1 November 2016</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://riceinstitute.org/research/revealed-preference-for-open-defecation-evidence-from-a-new-survey-in-rural-north-india-longer-working-paper/|title=Revealed Preference for Open Defecation: Evidence from a new survey in rural north India (longer working paper) {{!}} r.i.c.e.|website=riceinstitute.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref>\n* Lack of [[Behavior change (public health)|behavior change]]: Some communities have toilets, yet people prefer to defecate in the open.<ref name=\"Cavill\" /> In some cases, these toilets are provided by the government or other organizations and the people do not like them, or do not value them. They continue to defecate in the open. Also, older people are often found to defecate in the open and they are hesitant to change their behavior and go inside a closed toilet.<ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* Prefer being in nature: This happens mostly in less populated or rural areas, where people walk outside early in the morning and go to defecate in the fields or bushes. They prefer to be in nature and the fresh air; instead of defecating in a closed space such as a toilet.<ref name=\"Ahmad\" /> There may be cultural or habitual preference for defecating \"in the open air\", beside a local river or stream, or even the bush.\n* Combining open defecation with other activities: Some people walk early in the morning to look after their farms. Some consider it as a social activity, especially women who like to take some time to go out of their homes. While on their way to the fields for open defecation they can talk to other women and take care of their animals.<ref name=\"Routray 880\" />\n* [[Norm (social)|Social norms]]: Open defecation is a part of people's life and daily habit in some regions (e.g. in India). It is an ancient practice and is hard for many people to stop practicing. It is a part of a routine or social norm. In some cultures, there may be social taboos where a father-in-law may not use the same toilet as daughter-in-law in the same household.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n* [[Fecal incontinence]]: This medical condition can result in abrupt 'emergencies' and not enough time to access a toilet.\n\n=== Public defecation for other reasons ===\n\nIn [[Developed country|developed countries]], open defecation is either due to [[homelessness]], or considered to be a part of voluntary, recreational outdoor activities in remote areas. It is difficult to estimate how many people practice open defecation in these communities.\n\n[[The Mad Pooper]] is the name given to an unidentified woman who regularly defecated in public places while jogging during summer 2017 in the U.S. city of [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]].\n\n== India & Hinduism ==\nStreet defecation is an extreme epidemic in India.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Zakaria|first=Rafia| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/153549/indias-futile-war-open-defecation|title=India\u2019s Futile War on Open Defecation|date=2019-04-11|work=The New Republic|access-date=2020-04-13|issn=0028-6583}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unicef.in/Whatwedo/11/Eliminate-Open-Defecation|title=Eliminate Open Defecation {{!}} UNICEF|website=unicef.in|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Dinnoo |first=Shannti | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27775327|title=Why do millions of Indians defecate in the open?|date=2014-06-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-GB}}</ref> Scientific studies on this have shown Hinduism might be partially responsible.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vyas S, Spears D | title = Sanitation and Religion in South Asia: What Accounts for Differences across Countries? | journal = The Journal of Development Studies | volume = 54 | issue = 11 | pages = 2119\u20132135 | date = 2018-11-02 | pmid = 30363925 | pmc = 6183933 | doi = 10.1080/00220388.2018.1469742 | url = https://doi.org/10.1080/00220388.2018.1469742 }}</ref> Higher populations of Hinduism is coorelated with more open defecation. The rates are much lower in non-Hindu areas, as well as areas where Hindus live in majority non-Hindu areas, where social pressure promotes more toilet use.\n\nA similar study from Nepal on what motivates open defecation among Hindus. Several hindu men & women were interviewed, and asked why they choose open defecation over using toilets. Responses were it was a good social activity, and brings people together for conversations. Others describe that, it make them feel independent, as they could choose different ways. As well as it being a dominant social practice, and they never imagined a day where people would use toilets in enclosed indoor bathrooms. Another respondent said, he found toilets impossible to use, and did not like the idea of being in an enclosed room.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bhatt N, Budhathoki SS, Lucero-Prisno DE, Shrestha G, Bhattachan M, Thapa J, Sunny AK, Upadhyaya P, Ghimire A, Pokharel PK | display-authors = 6 | title = What motivates open defecation? A qualitative study from a rural setting in Nepal | journal = PloS One | volume = 14 | issue = 7 | pages = e0219246 | date = 2019-07-01 | pmid = 31260506 | pmc = 6602253 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0219246 | url = https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0219246 }}</ref>\n\nSome argued that using toilets was a religious violation, as they cannot do it at home where they have their religious idols, such as Tulsi plants which have religious significance in Hinduism. They also stated that in Hinduism it never mentions toilets, and they consider using toilets to be unhygienic.<ref name=\":3\" /> In some villages, Hindu villagers began worshipping newly built toilets instead of using them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.planetcustodian.com/indian-villagers-worshiping-newly-built-toilets-instead-of-using-them/7873/|title=Indian Villagers Worshiping Newly Built Toilets Instead of Using Them|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nMore findings from India show that, Hindu men view open defecation as a sign of their masculinity, and using toilets as childlike and feminine.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Clair RP, Rastogi R, Lee S, Clawson RA, Blatchley ER, Erdmann C | title = A Dialectical and Dialogical Approach to Health Policies and Programs: The Case of Open Defecation in India | journal = Health Communication | volume = 34 | issue = 11 | pages = 1231\u20131241 | date = October 2019 | pmid = 29764196 | doi = 10.1080/10410236.2018.1473705 | url = https://doi.org/10.1080/10410236.2018.1473705 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Clair |first=Robin Patric |last2=Rastogi |first2=Rahul |last3=Lee |first3=Seungyoon |last4=Clawson |first4=Rosalee A. |last5=Blatchley |first5=Ernest R. |last6=Erdmann |first6=Charlotte | name-list-format = vanc |date=2018-01-01|title=A qualitative study of communication, cultural identity, and open defecation|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/17459435.2018.1476906|journal=Qualitative Research Reports in Communication|volume=19|issue=1|pages=51\u201361|doi=10.1080/17459435.2018.1476906|issn=1745-9435}}</ref>\n\n== Prevalence and trends ==\n\nThe practice of open defecation is s [[Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation|and Sanitation]] (JMP) of UNICEF and WHO has been collecting data regarding open defecation prevalence worldwide. The figures are segregated by rural and urban areas and by levels of poverty. This program is tasked to monitor progress towards the millennium development goal (MDG) relating to drinking water and sanitation. As open defecation is one example of [[unimproved sanitation]], it is being monitored by JMP for each country and results published on a regular basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.wssinfo.org/data-estimates/|title = Data and estimates|access-date = 12 March 2015|website = JMP \u2013 WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply and Sanitation|publisher = WHO/UNICEF|url-status = dead|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150219114756/http://www.wssinfo.org/data-estimates|archive-date = 19 February 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"JMP2017\">WHO and UNICEF (2017) [https://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library/details/2805 Progress on Drinking Water, Sanitation and Hygiene: 2017 Update and SDG Baselines]. Geneva: World Health Organization (WHO) and the United Nations Children\u2019s Fund (UNICEF)</ref> The figures on open defecation used to be lumped together with other figures on unimproved sanitation but are collected separately since 2010.\n\nThe current estimate is that  around 673 million people practise open defecation.<ref name=\"JMP2019\"/>{{rp|74}}\n\nIn San Francisco (United States), open defecation complaints for street feces increased fivefold from 2011 to 2018, with 28,084 cases reported.<ref>{{cite web | title = San Francisco plans to power-wash the poop out of the Tenderloin | url = https://www.sfgate.com/local/article/City-plans-to-power-wash-the-poop-out-of-the-14878629.php | first = Mike | last = Moffitt | name-list-format = vanc | work = SFGATE | date = 3 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe number of people practicing open defecation fell from 20 percent in 2000 to 12 percent in 2015.<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />{{rp|page=34}} In 2016, the estimate was for 892 million people with no sanitation facility whatsoever and therefore practising open defecation (in gutters, behind bushes, in open water bodies etc.). Most people (9 of 10) who practice open defecation live in rural areas, but the vast majority lives in two regions ([[Central Asia]] and [[South Asia]]).<ref name=\"JMP2017\" /> In 2016, seventy-six percent (678 million) of the 892 million people practicing open defecation in the world lived in just seven countries.<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />\n\nThe countries with large numbers of people who openly defecate are listed in the table below.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+People practicing open defecation by country \u2013 in alphabetical order (use up and down arrows to order by numbers). The figures in column 2 and 3 are from 2015, as reported in 2017 by [[Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation|JMP]]<ref name=\"JMP2017\" /> and made accessible on several websites<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SH.STA.ODFC.ZS|title=People practicing open defecation (% of population)|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Country\n!Total country population (in thousands) in 2015 as reported in 2017 by JMP<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | Percentage of people who defecate in the open and absolute numbers (data from 2015 as reported in 2017 by JMP<ref name=\"JMP2017\" />)\n!More recent estimates of people defecating in the open (not JMP data but government data)\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Chad]]\n| 14,037\n| 68% Or 10 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | China\n| 1,376,049\n| 2% Or 28 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Eritrea]]\n| 5,228\n| 76% Or 4 million\n|\n|- Class=\"sortbottom\"\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Ethiopia\n| 99,391\n| 27% Or 27 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | India\n| 1,311,051\n| 39.84% Or 524 million\n| Developments since 2017:\n\n* 6.6% Or 88 millions in 2018 according to NRASS conducted by Independent Verificatiom Agency (IVA) of World Bank<ref>{{Cite News|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=178030|title=Independent Verification of Swachh Bharat Gramin confirms 93% usage of toilets|date = 27 March 2018|access-date = 11 March 2019|newspaper = Press Information Bureau}}</ref>\n* 1.4% Or 19 million in January 2019<br>according to government data<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|title = Swachh Bharat Mission \u2013 Gramin|url = http://swachhbharatmission.gov.in/sbmcms/index.htm|access-date = 15 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uniindia.com/over-83-9-million-toilets-constructed-under-swachh-bharat-mission/india/news/1350692.html|title=Over 83 9 million toilets constructed under Swachh Bharat Mission|access-date=14 September 2018|publisher=UNI India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/blogs/the-needles-eye/cleaning-up-india-with-gandhiji/|title=Cleaning Up India With Gandhiji|access-date=20 September 2018|publisher=Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Indonesia\n| 257,564\n| 12% Or 31 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Niger\n| 19,899\n| 71% Or 14 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Nigeria\n| 182,202\n| 26% Or 47 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Pakistan\n| 188,925\n| 12% Or 23 million\n|\n* 11.5% Or 21.8 million in 2015 as per WaterAid report<ref>{{Cite news|title = 79m Pakistanis still lack a decent toilet: report|url = https://dailytimes.com.pk/145728/79m-pakistanis-still-lack-decent-toilet-report/|date = November 23, 2017|access-date = September 21, 2019|newspaper = [[Daily Times (Pakistan)]]}}</ref>\n* 21.7% Or 41 million in 2015 as per UNICEF<ref>{{Cite news|title = Pakistan among 10 worst countries for access to toilets|url = https://www.dawn.com/news/1168181|date = March 8, 2015|access-date = September 21, 2019|newspaper = [[Dawn (newspaper)|The Dawn]]}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[South Sudan]]\n| 12,340\n| 61% Or 8 million\n|\n|-\n| Style=\"text-align:left;\" | Sudan\n| 40,235\n| 27% Or 11 million\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n== Impacts ==\n\n[[File:Dirty pit latrine in Mongolia in winter (5321157342).jpg|thumb|upright|A dirty pit latrine in Mongolia leading people to choose open defecation instead]]\n\n=== Public health ===\n{{Further|Sanitation#Health_aspects}}\n\nThe negative [[public health]] impacts of open defecation are the same as those described when there is no access to [[sanitation]] at all. Open defecation\u2014and lack of [[sanitation]] and [[hygiene]] in general\u2014is an important factor that cause various diseases; the most common being [[infectious diarrhea|diarrhea]] and [[helminthiasis|intestinal worm infections]] but also [[typhoid]], [[cholera]], [[hepatitis]], [[polio]], [[trachoma]], and others.<ref name=\"UN2015\">{{cite web|title=Call to action on sanitation|url=http://sanitationdrive2015.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSG_Sanitation_Fast-Facts_final.pdf|website=United Nations|access-date=15 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ChaturvediSpears2013\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Spears D, Ghosh A, Cumming O | title = Open defecation and childhood stunting in India: an ecological analysis of new data from 112 districts | journal = PloS One | volume = 8 | issue = 9 | pages = e73784 | year = 2013 | pmid = 24066070 | pmc = 3774764 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0073784 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, infectious diarrhea resulted in about 0.7 million deaths in children under five years old and 250 million lost school days.<ref name=\"UN2015\" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Walker CL, Rudan I, Liu L, Nair H, Theodoratou E, Bhutta ZA, O'Brien KL, Campbell H, Black RE | display-authors = 6 | title = Global burden of childhood pneumonia and diarrhoea | journal = Lancet | volume = 381 | issue = 9875 | pages = 1405\u20131416 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23582727 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(13)60222-6 }}</ref> It can also lead to [[Undernutrition in children|malnutrition]] and [[stunted growth]] among children.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Spears D, Ghosh A, Cumming O | title = Open defecation and childhood stunting in India: an ecological analysis of new data from 112 districts | journal = PloS One | volume = 8 | issue = 9 | pages = e73784 | date = 2013-09-16 | pmid = 24066070 | pmc = 3774764 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0073784 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mara|first=Duncan | name-list-format = vanc |date=2017-03-01|title=The elimination of open defecation and its adverse health effects: a moral imperative for governments and development professionals|url=http://washdev.iwaponline.com/content/7/1/1|journal=Journal of Water Sanitation and Hygiene for Development|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=1\u201312|doi=10.2166/washdev.2017.027|issn=2043-9083}}</ref>\n\nCertain diseases are grouped together under the name of [[waterborne diseases]], which are diseases transmitted via fecal pathogens in water. Open defecation can lead to [[water pollution]] when rain flushes feces that are dispersed in the environment into [[surface water]] or unprotected [[water well|wells]].\n\nOpen defecation was found by the [[WHO]] in 2014 to be a leading cause of diarrheal death. An average of 2,000 children under the age of five die every day from diarrhea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs330/en/ |title=WHO &#124; Diarrhoeal disease |publisher=World Health Organization |date=2013 |access-date=10 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nYoung children are particularly vulnerable to ingesting feces of other people that are lying around after open defecation, because young children crawl on the ground, walk barefoot, and put things in their mouths without washing their hands. Feces of farm animals are equally a cause of concern when children are playing in the yard.\n\nThose countries where open defecation is most widely practiced have the highest numbers of deaths of children under the age of five, as well as high levels of malnourishment (leading to [[stunted growth]] in children), high levels of poverty and large disparities between rich and poor.<ref name=\"JMP2014\" />\n\nResearch from India has shown that detrimental health impacts (particularly for early life health) are even more significant from open defecation when the population density is high: \"The same amount of open defecation is twice as bad in a place with a high population density average like India versus a low population density average like sub-Saharan Africa.\"<ref>{{cite book| last1=Vyas|date=2014| url=http://www.susana.org/_resources/documents/default/3-2089-16-1414062223.pdf|title=Population density and the effect of sanitation on early-life health], slide 19 (presentation at UNC conference in Oct. 2014)|publisher= Research Institute for Compassionate Economics, project (r.i.c.e.)}}</ref>\n\n=== Safety of women ===\n\nThere are strong gender impacts connected with open defecation. The lack of safe, private toilets makes women and girls vulnerable to violence and is an impediment to girls' education.<ref name=\":1\" /> Women are at risk of sexual molestation and rape as they search for places for open defecation that are secluded and private, often during hours of darkness.<ref>Lennon, S. (2011). [http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1758 Fear and anger: Perceptions of risks related to sexual violence against women linked to water and sanitation in Delhi, India] \u2013 Briefing Note. SHARE (Sanitation and Hygiene Applied Research for Equity) and WaterAid, UK </ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite book | last1 = House | first1 = Sarah | first2 = Suzanne | last2 = Ferron | first3 = Marni | last3 = Sommer | first4 = Sue | last4 = Cavill | name-list-format = vanc | date = 2014 | url = http://violence-wash.lboro.ac.uk/ | title = Violence, Gender & WASH: A Practitioner\u2019s Toolkit&nbsp;\u2013 Making water, sanitation and hygiene safer through improved programming and services | location = London, UK | publisher = WaterAid/SHARE }}</ref>\n\nLack of [[privacy]] has an especially large effect on the safety and sense of dignity of women and girls in developing countries. They face the shame of having to defecate in public so often wait until nightfall to relieve themselves. They risk being attacked after dark, though it means painfully holding their bladder and bowels all day.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|last1=Cavill|first1=Sue | name-list-format = vanc |title=Violence, gender and WASH: A practitioner's toolkit: Making Water, Sanitation and hygiene safer through improved programming and services|url=http://violence-wash.lboro.ac.uk/|publisher=WaterAid, SHARE Research Consortium|access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite journal|last1=Lennon|first1=Shirley | name-list-format = vanc |title=Fear and anger: Perceptions of risks related to sexual violence against women linked to water and sanitation in Delhi, India|journal=SHARE (Sanitation and Hygiene Applied Research for Equity) and WaterAid, UK|date=November 2011|url=http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1758|access-date=7 October 2015}}</ref> Women in developing countries increasingly express fear of assault or rape when having to leave the house after dark. Reports of attacks or harassment near or in toilet facilities, as well as near or in areas where women defecate openly, are common.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n== Prevention ==\n\nThere are several drivers used to eradicate open defecation, one of which is behaviour change. SaniFOAM (Focus on Opportunity, Ability and Motivation) is a conceptual framework which was developed specifically to address issues of sanitation and hygiene. Using focus, opportunity, ability and motivation as categories of determinants, SaniFOAM model identifies barriers to latrine adoption while simultaneously serving as a tool for designing, monitoring and evaluating sanitation interventions.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Introducing Sanifoam: A Framework to Analyze Sanitation Behaviors to Design Effective Sanitation Programs| vauthors = Devine J |publisher=World Bank|year=2009|isbn=|location=Washington, DC, USA|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| vauthors = Devine J |year=2010|title=Beyond tippt-taps: The role of enabling products in scaling up and sustaining handwashing|url=|journal=Waterlines|volume=29|issue=4|pages=304\u2013314|doi=10.3362/1756-3488.2010.033}}</ref> The following are some of the key drivers used to fight against open defecation in addition to behavior change:<ref name=\"Ahmad\" />\n\n* Political will\n* Sanitation solutions that offer a better value than open defecation\n* Stronger public sector local service delivery systems\n* Creation of the right incentive structures\n\n=== Integrated initiatives ===\n\nEfforts to reduce open defecation are more or less the same as those to achieve the MDG target on access to [[sanitation]]. A key aspect is awareness raising (for example via the UN [[World Toilet Day]] at a global level), behaviour change campaigns, increasing political will as well as demand for sanitation. [[Community-Led Total Sanitation]] (CLTS) campaigns have placed a particular focus on ending open defecation by \"triggering\" the communities themselves into action.<ref name=\"fieldnotes\">{{cite web|title=Field Notes: UNICEF Policy and Programming in Practice|url=http://www.unicef.org/socialpolicy/files/Field_Note_-_Community_Approaches_to_Total_Sanitation.pdf|website=UNICEF|access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2014, UNICEF began a multimedia campaign against open defecation in India, urging citizens to \"[[Poo2Loo|take their poo to the loo]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poo2loo.com/ |title=Why take poo to the loo |publisher=Poo2Loo |date= |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Simple sanitation technology options ===\n\n[[File:Photo by Ashley Wheaton, May 2011 (6376606733).jpg|thumb|Residents in [[Mymensingh]], Bangladesh participate in a workshop to discover more about mobile sanitation options (MoSan) as an alternative to open defecation]]\n\nThere are some simple sanitation technology options available to reduce open defecation prevalence if the open defecation behavior is due to not having toilets in the household and shared toilets being too far or too dangerous to reach, e.g., at night.\n\n==== Toilet bags ====\n\nPeople might already use plastic bags (also called [[flying toilet]]s) at night to contain their feces. However, a more advanced solution of the plastic toilet bag has been provided by the Swedish company Peepoople who are producing the \"Peepoo bag\", a \"personal, single-use, self-sanitizing, fully biodegradable toilet that prevents feces from contaminating the immediate area as well as the surrounding ecosystem\".<ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Wheaton A | date = 2009 | url = http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1125 | title = Results of a medium-scale trial of single-use, self-sanitising toilet bags in poor urban settlements in Bangladesh | publisher = Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Technische Zusammenarbeit GmbH (GTZ) | location = Dhaka, Bangladesh }}</ref> This bag is now being used in humanitarian responses, schools, and urban slums in developing countries.<ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Owako E | date = 2012 | url = http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1612 | title = Nyando peepoo trial project report | publisher = Kenya Red Cross | location = Kenya }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Naeem K, Berndtsson M | date = 2011 | url = http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1611 | title = Peepoo Try Pakistan \u2013 Sindh Floods | date = November 2011 | publisher = UN-HABITAT | location = Pakistan }}</ref>\n\n==== Bucket toilets and urine diversion ====\n\n[[Bucket toilet]]s are a simple [[portable toilet]] option. They can be upgraded in various ways, one of them being [[urine diversion]] which can make them similar to [[urine-diverting dry toilet]]s. Urine diversion can significantly reduce odors from [[dry toilet]]s. Examples of using this type of toilet to reduce open defecation are the \"MoSan\"<ref>Mijthab M., Woods E., Lokey H., Foote A., Rieck. C (2013). [http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/2021 Sanivation and MoSan Toilet \u2013 4 week Service Pilot in Karagita Naivasha, Kenya]. GIZ and Sanivation</ref> toilet (used in Kenya) or the urine-diverting dry toilet promoted by [[Sustainable Organic Integrated Livelihoods|SOIL]]<ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Russel K | date = 2013 | url = http://www.susana.org/en/resources/library/details/1753 | title = Mobile sanitation services for dense urban slums \u2013 Various documents on results from research grant. | publisher = Stanford University | location = U.S. }}</ref> in Haiti.\n\n=== Media ===\n\nThe mainstream media in some affected countries have recently been picking up on this issue of open defecation, for example, in India<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-29502603 |title=Why India's sanitation crisis needs more than toilets |publisher=[[BBC]] |date= 2014-10-06|access-date=10 March 2015|work=BBC News |last1=Biswas |first1=Soutik | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-india-has-highest-number-of-people-practicing-open-defecation-2036591 |title=India has highest number of people practicing open defecation &#124|publisher=[[DNA India]]|date=19 November 2014 |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref> and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1168181 |title=More than 40m Pakistanis defecate openly: Unicef \u2013 Pakistan |publisher=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |date= 2015-03-08|access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/850024/lack-of-toilets-tied-to-stunted-growth-in-pakistan-unicef/ |title=Lack of toilets tied to stunted growth in Pakistan: UNICEF |publisher=[[Express Tribune]] |date=13 March 2012 |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-6-215001-Over-43-million-people-in-Pakistan-defecate-in-the-open |title=Over 43 million people in Pakistan defecate in the open |publisher=[[The News International]] |date= |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal status ===\n\nIn certain jurisdictions, open or public defecation is a criminal offense which can be punished with a fine or even imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.municode.com/oh/columbus/codes/code_of_ordinances?nodeId=TIT23GEOFCO_CH2317PUCO_2317.14PUURDE|title=Municode Library|website=library.municode.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.columbuscriminalattorney.com/alcohol-offenses/public-urination-defecation/|title=Public Urination/Defecation \u2013 Columbus Criminal Attorney|date=2012-08-13|work=Columbus Criminal Attorney|access-date=2018-01-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wnep.com/2017/09/19/mad-pooper-jogger-wanted-for-repeatedly-defecating-in-colorado-front-yards/|title='Mad Pooper': Jogger Wanted for Defecating in Front Yards of Colorado Homes|date=2017-09-19|work=WNEP.com|access-date=2018-01-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2014/12/01/the-world-is-not-your-toilet-police-note.html|title=The world is NOT your toilet, Columbus police note | last = Allison | first = Manning | name-list-format = vanc |work=The Columbus Dispatch|access-date=2018-01-30 }}</ref>\n\n=== In popular culture ===\n\n[[David Sedaris]]' essay \"Adventures At Poo Corner\" dealt with people who openly defecate in commercial businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/303/david-and-goliath/act-three|title=Adventures At Poo Corner|date=2017-12-12|website=This American Life|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Free Bleeding]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{offline|med}}\n\n* [http://opendefecation.org/news/ UN Call to action to end open defecation]\n* [http://www.susana.org/en/knowledge-hub/resources-and-publications/library?search=open+defecation Documents about open defecation] in library of [[Sustainable Sanitation Alliance]]\n\n{{Toilets}}\n\n{{Pollution}}\n\n{{Public health}}\n\n{{Waste}}\n\n[[Category:Sanitation]]\n[[Category:Defecation]]\n", "name_user": "Hari147", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 950911955 byArjayay(talk) Clear racial biasness and continuous reverts by an experienced editor is appalling and disgraceful)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open_defecation"}
{"title_page": "2016 Iowa Democratic caucuses", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2016 Iowa Democratic caucuses\n| country = Iowa\n| flag_image = Flag of Iowa (xrmap collection).svg\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = Iowa Democratic caucuses, 2012\n| previous_year = 2012\n| election_date = {{Start date|2016|02|01}}\n| next_election = 2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses\n| next_year = 2020\n| votes_for_election = 51 [[2016 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]] delegates<br/>(44 pledged, 7 unpledged)\n| image1 = [[File:Hillary Clinton by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|120px]]\n| candidate1 = '''[[Hillary Clinton]]'''\n| home_state1 = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| delegate_count1 = '''23'''\n| percentage1 = '''49.84%'''\n| map_image = Iowa Democratic presidential caucus election, 2016.svg\n| map_size = 300px\n| map_caption = Iowa results by county (state delegate equivalents) {{legend|#d4aa00|Hillary Clinton}}\n{{legend|#228B22|Bernie Sanders}}{{legend|#666666|Tie}}\n| color1 = d4aa00\n| image2 = [[File:Bernie Sanders September 2015 cropped.jpg|120px]]\n| candidate2 = [[Bernie Sanders]]\n| color2 = 228B22\n| home_state2 = [[Vermont]]\n| delegate_count2 = 21\n| percentage2 = 49.59%\n| elected_members = [[2016 New Hampshire Democratic primary|NH]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2016 Iowa Democratic caucuses''' took place on February 1 in [[Iowa]], as usual marking the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]'s first nominating contest in their series of [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|presidential primaries]] ahead of the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].\n\nThe [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] held its own [[Iowa Republican caucuses, 2016|Iowa caucuses]] on the same day.\n\nDespite a late challenge, [[Hillary Clinton]] was able to defeat [[Bernie Sanders]] in the first-in-the-nation [[Iowa caucuses|Iowa Caucus]] by the closest margin in the history of the contest: 49.8% to 49.6% (Clinton collected 700.47 state delegate equivalents to Sanders' 696.92, a difference of one quarter of a percentage point).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2016/president/ia/iowa_democratic_presidential_caucus-3195.html|title=Election 2016 - Iowa Democratic Presidential Caucus|publisher=RealClearPolitics|accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> The victory, which was projected to award her 23 pledged national convention delegates (two more than Sanders), made Clinton the first woman to win the Caucus and marked a clear difference from 2008, where she finished in third place behind Obama and [[John Edwards]].<ref name=\"whotv.com\">{{cite web|url=http://whotv.com/2016/02/02/hillary-clinton-narrowly-defeats-bernie-sanders-in-iowa-democratic-caucuses/|title=All Precincts Reported: Clinton Defeats Sanders By Historically Small Margin|publisher=WHO-TV|location=Des Moines, Iowa|last1=Hepker|first1=Aaron|date=February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/election/2016/2/02/and-winner-iowa-caucus-hillary-clinton-barely|title=And the Winner of the Iowa Caucus Is: Hillary Clinton (Barely)|issn=0001-8996|work=The Advocate|last1=Ennis|first1=Dawn|date=February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/iowa|title=Iowa Caucus Results|date=February 27, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/primaries/IA|title=Iowa Caucus 2016: Election Results|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> [[Martin O'Malley]] suspended his campaign after a disappointing third-place finish with only 0.5% of the state delegate equivalents awarded, leaving Clinton and Sanders the only two major candidates in the race.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/02/01/465224058/martin-omalley-ends-presidential-bid|title=Martin O'Malley Ends Presidential Bid|date=February 1, 2016|publisher=NPR|author=Taylor, Jessica|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref>  171,517 people participated in the 2016 Iowa Democratic caucuses.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160206012214/http://iowademocrats.org/statement-from-idp-chair-on-tonights-historically-close-caucus-results/ Statement from IDP Chair on Tonight\u2019s Historically Close Caucus Results] Iowa Democratic Party. 2 February 2016.</ref>\n\n[[File:Hillary Clinton Iowa April 2015 20160802092059!.jpg|thumb|Hillary Clinton launched her campaign in Iowa, April 2015]]\n\n[[File:Bernie Sanders in January 2016 by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Bernie Sanders campaigns in Iowa in January 2016]]\n\n[[File:Sanders supporters in Iowa, January 31, 2016.jpg|thumb|Sanders supporters in Iowa, January 31, 2016]]\n\n==Procedure==\n{{Further|Walking subcaucus}}\n\nThere was no ballot; instead, a unique form of debate and groupings chose delegates to [[List of counties in Iowa|county]] conventions supporting [[Hillary Clinton]], [[Martin O'Malley]], and [[Bernie Sanders]]. The Iowa Democratic Party did not release vote counts or the numbers of these delegates. Instead, they released the estimated amount of state delegates supporting each candidate.<ref>http://iowademocrats.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/2016-IDP-Final-Precinct-Caucus-Results-PrecinctCandidateResults1.pdf</ref> The county conventions selected delegates to [[Iowa's congressional districts|district]] and state conventions, which in turn selected the delegates to the Democratic National Convention. The delegates at the county, district and state conventions were not pledged and were allowed to change their preference, meaning that the final result of the state delegates could have been different from what was estimated at the Iowa precinct caucuses.\n\nDelegates to the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]] were selected at district and state conventions. The [[Iowa's 1st congressional district|First]] and [[Iowa's 2nd congressional district|Second]] congressional districts received 8 district delegates, the [[Iowa's 3rd congressional district|Third]] received 7 and the [[Iowa's 4th congressional district|Fourth]] received 6. These district delegates were elected at the District Conventions based on the result in each Congressional District.<ref name=\"TGP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/P16/IA-D|title=The Green Papers: 2016 Presidential Primaries, Caucuses, and Conventions|website=The Green Papers}}</ref>\n\nAt the State Convention, the 15 statewide pledged delegates were elected based on the statewide results. 9 of these delegates were At-Large and 6 were Party Leaders and Elected Officials (PLEO) who were pledged based on the proportion of At-Large delegates supporting candidates.  The Iowa delegation also included 8 superdelegates who were not pledged based on the result of the caucus process, which included 1 [[U.S. Representative]] and 7 Democratic National Committee members.<ref name=\"TGP\" />\n\n==Debates and forums==\n\n===November 2015 debate in Des Moines===\n{{main|Second Democratic Party presidential debate, November 2015 in Des Moines, Iowa}}\n\nOn November 14, 2015, the Democratic Party held a second presidential debate at the Sheslow Auditorium at [[Drake University]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]]. Hosted by CBS News Political Director [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]], it aired on [[CBS News]] and was also broadcast by [[KCCI]] and ''[[The Des Moines Register]]''. With the remaining candidates Hillary Clinton, Bernie Sanders, and Martin O'Malley participating, it was the first debate to be broadcast over nationwide network television, the previous debate having gone over cable.<ref name=\"2nd\">{{cite web | url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/11/second-democratic-2016-debate-iowa-when-is-it-215792 | title=Everything you need to know about Saturday's Democratic debate | work=[[Politico]] | date=November 12, 2015 | accessdate=November 13, 2015 | author=Weiland, Noah}}</ref>\n\nAs the day before the debate, November 13, was the day of the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]], CBS announced that the debate would focus on foreign policy and terrorism.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/14/us/politics/democratic-debate-to-get-new-terrorism-focus-after-paris-attacks-cbs-says.html?_r=0|title=CBS Shifts Emphasis of Democratic Debate to Reflect Paris Attacks|work=New York Times|last1=Steel|first1=Emily|date=November 14, 2015|accessdate=November 15, 2015}}</ref> In addition, a moment of silence was held at the beginning of the debate in memory of the victims.\n\n===January 2016 forum in Des Moines===\n{{see also|Democratic Party presidential debates, 2016}}\nOn January 11, 2016 the \"Black and Brown\" forum was held at [[Drake University]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]]. Focusing on minority issues, it aired on [[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gold|first1=Hadas|authorlink=Hadas Gold|title=Fusion to host Democratic presidential forum|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/on-media/2015/11/fusion-to-host-democratic-presidential-forum-216075|website=Politico|publisher=Politico|accessdate=January 11, 2016|date=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Opinion polling==\n{{see also|Statewide opinion polling for the Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016}}\n{{Iowa Democratic primary polls, 2016}}\n\n==Results==\n\n{{2016IADem}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:12px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"| Iowa Democratic county conventions, March 13, 2016\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Candidate\n! colspan=\"2\" | State delegates\n! colspan=\"3\" | Estimated delegates\n|-\n! style=\"width:70px;\" | Count\n! style=\"width:80px;\" | Percentage\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Pledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Unpledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Total</small>\n|- {{party shading/Democratic}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton]]\n| 704\n| 50.07%\n| 23\n| 6\n| 29\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|Bernie Sanders]]\n| 700\n| 49.79%\n| 21\n| 0\n| 21\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Martin O'Malley presidential campaign, 2016|Martin O'Malley]]\n| 1\n| 0.07%\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Uncommitted\n| 1\n| 0.07%\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n|-\n! Total\n! 1,406\n! 100%\n! 44\n! 7\n! 51\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Source: ''[http://iowademocrats.org/iowa-democratic-county-convention-results/ Iowa Democrats]''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:12px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"| Iowa Democratic District conventions, April 30, 2016\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Candidate\n! colspan=\"2\" | State delegates\n! colspan=\"3\" | Estimated delegates\n|-\n! style=\"width:70px;\" | Count\n! style=\"width:80px;\" | Percentage\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Pledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Unpledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Total</small>\n|- {{party shading/Democratic}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton]]\n| 697\n| 50.40%\n| 23\n| 6\n| 29\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|Bernie Sanders]]\n| 686\n| 49.60%\n| 21\n| 0\n| 21\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Uncommitted\n| \n| \n| \n| 1\n| 1\n|-\n! Total\n! 1,383\n! 100%\n! 44\n! 7\n! 51\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Source: ''[http://iowademocrats.org/2016-iowa-district-convention-results/ Iowa Democrats]''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:12px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"| Iowa State Democratic Convention, June 18, 2016\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Candidate\n! colspan=\"2\" | State delegates\n! colspan=\"3\" | Estimated delegates\n|-\n! style=\"width:70px;\" | Count\n! style=\"width:80px;\" | Percentage\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Pledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Unpledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Total</small>\n|- {{party shading/Democratic}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton]]\n| 714\n| 55.56%\n| 23\n| 6\n| 29\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|Bernie Sanders]]\n| 571\n| 44.44%\n| 21\n| 0\n| 21\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Uncommitted\n| \n| \n| \n| 1\n| 1\n|-\n! Total\n! 1,285\n! 100%\n! 44\n! 7\n! 51\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Source: ''[http://iowademocrats.org/2016-iowa-democratic-party-state-convention-results/#more-15445 Iowa Democrats]''\n|}\n\nFollowing a poor result in the caucuses, [[Martin O'Malley presidential campaign, 2016|Martin O'Malley]] announced he was suspending his campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/02/us/politics/martin-o-malley-ends-presidential-campaign.html|title=Martin O'Malley to Drop Out After Finish in Iowa Vote|last=Parker|first=Ashley|date=2016-02-01|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-06-21}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n[[File:Iowa Democratic caucus results, 2016.svg|thumb|150px|Results of the Iowa Democratic caucus, 2016\n{{legend|#1666cb|Clinton\u201470-80%}}{{legend|#4389e3|Clinton\u201460-70%}}{{legend|#86b6f2|Clinton\u201450-60%}}{{legend|#b9d7ff|Clinton\u2014<50%}}{{legend|Purple|Tie between Clinton and Sanders}}{{legend|#f2b3be|Sanders\u2014<50%}}{{legend|#e27f90|Sanders\u201450-60%}}{{legend|#cc2f4a|Sanders\u201460-70%}}{{legend|#d40000|Sanders\u201470-80%}}]]\n\n\"[O]rganizational issues around the caucus\", including difficulty identifying volunteers to \"oversee individual precinct caucuses,\" contributed to a \"disorganized process that lent itself to chaos and conspiracy theories\" according to ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|title = Iowa Democratic party altered precinct's caucus results during chaotic night|url = https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/05/iowa-democratic-party-altered-precinct-caucus-results-clinton-sanders|newspaper = The Guardian|date = February 5, 2016|access-date = February 6, 2016|issn = 0261-3077|language = en-GB|first = Ben|last = Jacobs}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Both the Sanders and Clinton campaigns have flagged a very small number of concerns for us, and we are looking at them all on a case-by-case basis.|Sam Lau|Iowa Democratic Party}}\n\nAfter initially refusing to review caucus results, Iowa Democratic Party officials did end up \"making updates where discrepancies have been found.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Iowa margin between Clinton, Sanders shifts as errors found|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/05/iowa-margin-between-clinton-sanders-shifts-errors/79877898/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 5, 2016|last = Jacobs|first = Jennifer|date = February 5, 2016|publisher = The USA Today Network}}</ref> With \"doubts about which Democratic candidate actually won the Iowa caucuses,\" there have been \"fresh calls for the party to mirror the simple, secret-ballot method\" the Republicans use. Stated [[Norm Sterzenbach]], former Iowa Democratic Party executive director who oversaw five election cycles: \"It's worth discussing again, but it's not as simple as it sounds.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Uproar could lead to revamping Democratic caucuses|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/06/uproar-could-lead-revamping-democratic-caucuses/79910420/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 7, 2016|date = February 6, 2016|publisher = The USA Today Network|last = Jacobs|first = Jennifer}}</ref> It is said that Clinton won by the thinnest margin in the history of Iowa caucuses.\n\n=== Instances ===\n\nIowa Democrats reported \"discrepancies in caucus results\" and confusion over the math of the delegate-awarding system. In Grinnell Ward 1, 19 delegates were awarded to Sanders and seven to Clinton on caucus night. The Iowa Democratic party later shifted one delegate from Sanders to Clinton, but did not notify the precinct secretary, who \"only discovered that this happened the next day, when checking the precinct results in other parts of the county.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOther reported discrepancies included:\n* the lone caucusgoer in Woodbury County No. 43, who voted for Sanders\u2014but \"final results state\" Clinton won one county delegate and Sanders zero.\n* in Knoxville No. 3, where the count was 58 for Sanders and 52 for Clinton\u2014but official results showed Clinton with five county delegates and Sanders with four.\n* the four delegates in Cedar Rapids No. 9 precinct who split evenly between Sanders and Clinton\u2014but only 131 people signed in at the beginning of the caucus with two separate head counts showing 136 people voted.\nIn Des Moines No. 42, \"after everyone had formed initial groups for their preferred candidate,\" a Clinton supporter addressed O'Malley supporters and undecideds, telling them \"they could stay and realign or leave.\" Some mistakenly believed that meant voting was finished and left early without being counted.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Iowans claim instances when Sanders was shorted delegates|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/06/iowans-claim-instances-when-sanders-shorted-delegates/79902080/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 7, 2016|last = Jacobs|first = Jennifer|publisher = The USA Today Network|date = February 7, 2016}}</ref> In the same precinct, votes were still missing the morning after the caucus. Democrats \"from that neighborhood scrambled to find party officials\" to report that Sanders won by a margin of two delegates over Clinton. This narrowed Clinton's \"excruciatingly close lead\" even further\u2014bringing the tally for \"delegate equivalents\" at that point to Clinton 699.57, Sanders 697.77.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Missing precinct scrambles to report Sanders won|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/02/some-democratic-precinct-results-unaccounted/79682184/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Coin tosses===\n\n''[[The Des Moines Register]]'' reported \"an unknown number\" of county delegates awarded \"after the flip of a coin.\" Sam Lau, a spokesman for the Iowa Democratic Party, said seven coin flips were reported through \"the party's smartphone app\"\u2014but officials who reported county delegate totals via the app \"weren't required to signify if the win was the result of a coin toss.\" Lau said Bernie Sanders won six of these. The paper identified \"six coin flips through social media and one in an interview with a caucus participant\"\u2014with Clinton the apparent winner of six of these seven. Any overlap, or its impact on results, between the coin flips identified by the ''Register'' and those the party confirmed was not known.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/02/iowa-caucus-coin-flip-count-unknown/79708740/|title=Iowa caucus coin flip count unknown|accessdate = February 3, 2016|publisher = Des Moines Register|date = February 2, 2016|last = Clayworth|first = Jason|last2 = Noble|first2 = Jason|newspaper = The Des Moines Register}}</ref>\n\nAn Iowa Democratic Party official told [[NPR]] there were \"at least a dozen tiebreakers\" decided by a coin toss\u2014 and that \"Sen. Sanders won at least a handful.\"<ref>{{cite web|title = Coin-Toss Fact Check: No, Coin Flips Did Not Win Iowa For Hillary Clinton|url = https://www.npr.org/2016/02/02/465268206/coin-toss-fact-check-no-coin-flips-did-not-win-iowa-for-hillary-clinton|access-date = February 3, 2016|first = Domenico|last = Montanaro|publisher = [[NPR]]|date = February 2, 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160203073439/http://www.npr.org/2016/02/02/465268206/coin-toss-fact-check-no-coin-flips-did-not-win-iowa-for-hillary-clinton|archive-date = February 3, 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Gone unmentioned so far is that even if Clinton won that Miracle Six \u2014 and there were no other coin tosses \u2014 it would make little difference in the outcome. That is, in part, because of the complicated way Iowa Democrats allocate their delegates \u2014 and what was being reported on election night and what wasn't.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Coin-Toss Fact Check: No, Coin Flips Did Not Win Iowa For Hillary Clinton|url = https://www.npr.org/2016/02/02/465268206/coin-toss-fact-check-no-coin-flips-did-not-win-iowa-for-hillary-clinton|website = NPR.org|access-date = February 3, 2016|first = Domenico Montanaro|last = Twitter}}</ref>|Domenico Montanaro|NPR}}\n\n===Review===\n\nSanders' campaign \"launched\" a review of the results of the caucuses, citing as \"complicating factors\" the \"razor-thin margin\", the \"arcane\" caucusing rules, the reporting delays from some precincts, and the reporting technology used. The campaign is rechecking results precinct-by-precinct, reviewing \"math sheets or other paperwork\" precinct chairs used and were supposed to return to party officials\u2014then comparing these with results entered into the party's Microsoft app. Rania Batrice, a Sanders spokeswoman, challenged: \"Let's compare notes. Let's see if they match.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn an editorial, ''The Des Moines Register'' called for an audit of the results, declaring \"What happened Monday night at the Democratic caucuses was a debacle, period.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Editorial: Something smells in the Democratic Party|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/opinion/editorials/caucus/2016/02/03/editorial-something-smells-democratic-party/79777580/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 4, 2016}}</ref> First noting that only two-tenths of a percent separated Sanders and Clinton and \"much larger margins trigger automatic recounts in other states,\" they stated:\n\n<blockquote>Too many accounts have arisen of inconsistent counts, untrained and overwhelmed volunteers, confused voters, cramped precinct locations, a lack of voter registration forms and other problems. Too many of us, including members of the Register editorial board who were observing caucuses, saw opportunities for error amid Monday night's chaos.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>\n\nIn lieu of \"official paper records\" the party had \"declined to provide the campaign\"\u2014which would show individual precinct vote tallies before they were entered into the party's app the night of the caucuses\u2014the Sanders' campaign was contacting each of its own precinct captains to reconstruct caucus results.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Sanders campaign says it was denied paper records of Iowa caucus vote|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/sanders-campaign-says-it-was-denied-paper-records-of-iowa-caucus-vote/2016/02/04/fcdc8f46-cb93-11e5-88ff-e2d1b4289c2f_story.html|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = February 4, 2016|access-date = February 5, 2016|issn = 0190-8286|language = en-US|first = Tom|last = Hamburger}}</ref> Sanders' campaign manager Jeff Weaver said: \"I think everybody has an interest in making it as accurate as possible\", though \"[a]s an empirical matter, we're not likely to ever know what the actual result was\".<ref>{{Cite news|title = Sanders campaign reviewing Iowa caucus totals, says actual result may never be known|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/02/02/sanders-campaign-reviewing-iowa-caucus-totals-says-actual-result-may-never-be-known/|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = February 2, 2016|access-date = February 2, 2016|issn = 0190-8286|language = en-US|first = John|last = Wagner}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Let's not blow this out of proportion. This is not the biggest deal in the world. We think, by the way, based on talking to our precinct captains, we may have at least two more delegates.\"<ref name=\"Jacobs 6.2.16\">{{cite news|last1=Jacobs|first1=Ben|title=Iowa Democratic party altered precinct's caucus results during chaotic night|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/05/iowa-democratic-party-altered-precinct-caucus-results-clinton-sanders|accessdate=February 6, 2016|publisher=The Guardian|date=February 5, 2016}}</ref>|Bernie Sanders}}\n\n== Analysis ==\n[[File:Iowa Caucus Winners - political cartoon by DonkeyHotey (24653531072).jpg|thumb|Iowa Caucus Winners \u2013 political cartoon by DonkeyHotey]]\nDespite a late challenge from insurgent Senator Bernie Sanders of [[Vermont]], whose [[Populism|populist]] economic message resonated with Iowa's [[Progressivism|progressive]] Democratic electorate,{{According to whom|date=February 2017}} Clinton eked out a 0.2-percentage-point victory in the first-in-the-nation caucus, edging out Sanders by only four state delegate equivalents. As ''[[The New York Times]]'' described, Sanders' near-tie with Clinton combined with [[Ted Cruz]]'s [[Iowa Republican caucuses, 2016|Republican]] victory in the caucus demonstrated how the \"2016 campaign has turned to easing the palpable frustrations of a large portion of white working-class Americans who believe that the country no longer works for them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/02/us/iowa-caucus-results.html|title=Fury Shakes the Iowa Caucuses, Boosting Ted Cruz While Slowing Hillary Clinton|last=Barbaro|first=Michael|date=February 2, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to entrance polls, Clinton won the [[Caucasian race|white]] vote by a 49\u201346 margin against Sanders, with white voters comprising 91% of the Iowa electorate. She won [[non-white]] voters more resoundingly, 58\u201334. Sanders won among men, 50\u201344, but Clinton won women, 53-42. Sanders proved his immense strength with [[millennials]] by winning 17\u201329-year-olds 84-14, with Clinton winning [[Old age|senior citizens]], 69\u201326. Clinton won among voters who had a [[high school diploma]] or less, and among those who had a [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate degree]], while Sanders won voters with only a [[Academic degree|college degree]]. Sanders won 53-44 among voters who made an income of less than $50k per year, Clinton won more [[Wealth|affluent]] voters 52-42. In terms of political party affiliation, Clinton won [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] 56-39 but lost [[Independent Party (United States)|Independents]] to Bernie Sanders, 69\u201329.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/election/primaries/polls/ia/Dem|title=2016 Election Center \u2013 Presidential Primaries and Caucuses \u2013 2016 Election Center \u2013 CNNPolitics.com|website=CNN|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nUpon learning she had been awarded the state of Iowa after 1&nbsp;P.M. the following day, Clinton told [[CNN]]'s [[Wolf Blitzer]], \"My luck was not that good last time around, and it was wonderful to win the caucus, to have that experience.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/02/politics/new-hampshire-primary-2016/index.html|title=Hillary Clinton wins Iowa caucuses| first1=Tami | last1=Luhby | first2=Nia-Malika | last2=Henderson |date=February 3, 2016|website=CNN|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2016 Democratic primaries}}\n\n[[Category:2016 United States Democratic presidential primaries by state|Iowa]]\n[[Category:2016 Iowa elections|Democratic primary]]\n[[Category:Iowa Democratic caucuses|2016]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2016 Iowa Democratic caucuses\n| country = Iowa\n| flag_image = Flag of Iowa (xrmap collection).svg\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = Iowa Democratic caucuses, 2012\n| previous_year = 2012\n| election_date = {{Start date|2016|02|01}}\n| next_election = 2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses\n| next_year = 2020\n| votes_for_election = 51 [[2016 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]] delegates<br/>(44 pledged, 7 unpledged)\n| image1 = [[File:Hillary Clinton by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|120px]]\n| candidate1 = '''[[Hillary Clinton]]'''\n| home_state1 = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| delegate_count1 = '''23'''\n| percentage1 = '''49.84%'''\n| map_image = Iowa Democratic presidential caucus election, 2016.svg\n| map_size = 300px\n| map_caption  = Iowa results by county (state delegate equivalents) {{legend|#d4aa00|Hillary Clinton}}\n{{legend|#228B22|Bernie Sanders}}{{legend|#666666|Tie}}\n| color1 = d4aa00\n| image2 = [[File:Bernie Sanders September 2015 cropped.jpg|120px]]\n| candidate2 = [[Bernie Sanders]]\n| color2 = 228B22\n| home_state2 = [[Vermont]]\n| delegate_count2 = 21\n| percentage2 =49.59%\n}}\n\nThe '''2016 Iowa Democratic caucuses''' took place on February 1 in [[Iowa]], as usual marking the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]'s first nominating contest in their series of [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|presidential primaries]] ahead of the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].\n\nThe [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] held its own [[Iowa Republican caucuses, 2016|Iowa caucuses]] on the same day.\n\nDespite a late challenge, [[Hillary Clinton]] was able to defeat [[Bernie Sanders]] in the first-in-the-nation [[Iowa caucuses|Iowa Caucus]] by the closest margin in the history of the contest: 49.8% to 49.6% (Clinton collected 700.47 state delegate equivalents to Sanders' 696.92, a difference of one quarter of a percentage point).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2016/president/ia/iowa_democratic_presidential_caucus-3195.html|title=Election 2016 - Iowa Democratic Presidential Caucus|publisher=RealClearPolitics|accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> The victory, which was projected to award her 23 pledged national convention delegates (two more than Sanders), made Clinton the first woman to win the Caucus and marked a clear difference from 2008, where she finished in third place behind Obama and [[John Edwards]].<ref name=\"whotv.com\">{{cite web|url=http://whotv.com/2016/02/02/hillary-clinton-narrowly-defeats-bernie-sanders-in-iowa-democratic-caucuses/|title=All Precincts Reported: Clinton Defeats Sanders By Historically Small Margin|publisher=WHO-TV|location=Des Moines, Iowa|last1=Hepker|first1=Aaron|date=February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/election/2016/2/02/and-winner-iowa-caucus-hillary-clinton-barely|title=And the Winner of the Iowa Caucus Is: Hillary Clinton (Barely)|issn=0001-8996|work=The Advocate|last1=Ennis|first1=Dawn|date=February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/iowa|title=Iowa Caucus Results|date=February 27, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/primaries/IA|title=Iowa Caucus 2016: Election Results|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> [[Martin O'Malley]] suspended his campaign after a disappointing third-place finish with only 0.5% of the state delegate equivalents awarded, leaving Clinton and Sanders the only two major candidates in the race.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/02/01/465224058/martin-omalley-ends-presidential-bid|title=Martin O'Malley Ends Presidential Bid|date=February 1, 2016|publisher=NPR|author=Taylor, Jessica|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref>  171,517 people participated in the 2016 Iowa Democratic caucuses.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160206012214/http://iowademocrats.org/statement-from-idp-chair-on-tonights-historically-close-caucus-results/ Statement from IDP Chair on Tonight\u2019s Historically Close Caucus Results] Iowa Democratic Party. 2 February 2016.</ref>\n\n[[File:Hillary Clinton Iowa April 2015 20160802092059!.jpg|thumb|Hillary Clinton launched her campaign in Iowa, April 2015]]\n\n[[File:Bernie Sanders in January 2016 by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Bernie Sanders campaigns in Iowa in January 2016]]\n\n[[File:Sanders supporters in Iowa, January 31, 2016.jpg|thumb|Sanders supporters in Iowa, January 31, 2016]]\n\n==Procedure==\n{{Further|Walking subcaucus}}\n\nThere was no ballot; instead, a unique form of debate and groupings chose delegates to [[List of counties in Iowa|county]] conventions supporting [[Hillary Clinton]], [[Martin O'Malley]], and [[Bernie Sanders]]. The Iowa Democratic Party did not release vote counts or the numbers of these delegates. Instead, they released the estimated amount of state delegates supporting each candidate.<ref>http://iowademocrats.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/2016-IDP-Final-Precinct-Caucus-Results-PrecinctCandidateResults1.pdf</ref> The county conventions selected delegates to [[Iowa's congressional districts|district]] and state conventions, which in turn selected the delegates to the Democratic National Convention. The delegates at the county, district and state conventions were not pledged and were allowed to change their preference, meaning that the final result of the state delegates could have been different from what was estimated at the Iowa precinct caucuses.\n\nDelegates to the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]] were selected at district and state conventions. The [[Iowa's 1st congressional district|First]] and [[Iowa's 2nd congressional district|Second]] congressional districts received 8 district delegates, the [[Iowa's 3rd congressional district|Third]] received 7 and the [[Iowa's 4th congressional district|Fourth]] received 6. These district delegates were elected at the District Conventions based on the result in each Congressional District.<ref name=\"TGP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/P16/IA-D|title=The Green Papers: 2016 Presidential Primaries, Caucuses, and Conventions|website=The Green Papers}}</ref>\n\nAt the State Convention, the 15 statewide pledged delegates were elected based on the statewide results. 9 of these delegates were At-Large and 6 were Party Leaders and Elected Officials (PLEO) who were pledged based on the proportion of At-Large delegates supporting candidates.  The Iowa delegation also included 8 superdelegates who were not pledged based on the result of the caucus process, which included 1 [[U.S. Representative]] and 7 Democratic National Committee members.<ref name=\"TGP\" />\n\n==Debates and forums==\n\n===November 2015 debate in Des Moines===\n{{main|Second Democratic Party presidential debate, November 2015 in Des Moines, Iowa}}\n\nOn November 14, 2015, the Democratic Party held a second presidential debate at the Sheslow Auditorium at [[Drake University]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]]. Hosted by CBS News Political Director [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]], it aired on [[CBS News]] and was also broadcast by [[KCCI]] and ''[[The Des Moines Register]]''. With the remaining candidates Hillary Clinton, Bernie Sanders, and Martin O'Malley participating, it was the first debate to be broadcast over nationwide network television, the previous debate having gone over cable.<ref name=\"2nd\">{{cite web | url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/11/second-democratic-2016-debate-iowa-when-is-it-215792 | title=Everything you need to know about Saturday's Democratic debate | work=[[Politico]] | date=November 12, 2015 | accessdate=November 13, 2015 | author=Weiland, Noah}}</ref>\n\nAs the day before the debate, November 13, was the day of the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]], CBS announced that the debate would focus on foreign policy and terrorism.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/14/us/politics/democratic-debate-to-get-new-terrorism-focus-after-paris-attacks-cbs-says.html?_r=0|title=CBS Shifts Emphasis of Democratic Debate to Reflect Paris Attacks|work=New York Times|last1=Steel|first1=Emily|date=November 14, 2015|accessdate=November 15, 2015}}</ref> In addition, a moment of silence was held at the beginning of the debate in memory of the victims.\n\n===January 2016 forum in Des Moines===\n{{see also|Democratic Party presidential debates, 2016}}\nOn January 11, 2016 the \"Black and Brown\" forum was held at [[Drake University]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]]. Focusing on minority issues, it aired on [[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gold|first1=Hadas|authorlink=Hadas Gold|title=Fusion to host Democratic presidential forum|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/on-media/2015/11/fusion-to-host-democratic-presidential-forum-216075|website=Politico|publisher=Politico|accessdate=January 11, 2016|date=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Opinion polling==\n{{see also|Statewide opinion polling for the Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016}}\n{{Iowa Democratic primary polls, 2016}}\n\n==Results==\n\n{{2016IADem}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:12px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"| Iowa Democratic county conventions, March 13, 2016\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Candidate\n! colspan=\"2\" | State delegates\n! colspan=\"3\" | Estimated delegates\n|-\n! style=\"width:70px;\" | Count\n! style=\"width:80px;\" | Percentage\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Pledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Unpledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Total</small>\n|- {{party shading/Democratic}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton]]\n| 704\n| 50.07%\n| 23\n| 6\n| 29\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|Bernie Sanders]]\n| 700\n| 49.79%\n| 21\n| 0\n| 21\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Martin O'Malley presidential campaign, 2016|Martin O'Malley]]\n| 1\n| 0.07%\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Uncommitted\n| 1\n| 0.07%\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n|-\n! Total\n! 1,406\n! 100%\n! 44\n! 7\n! 51\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Source: ''[http://iowademocrats.org/iowa-democratic-county-convention-results/ Iowa Democrats]''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:12px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"| Iowa Democratic District conventions, April 30, 2016\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Candidate\n! colspan=\"2\" | State delegates\n! colspan=\"3\" | Estimated delegates\n|-\n! style=\"width:70px;\" | Count\n! style=\"width:80px;\" | Percentage\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Pledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Unpledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Total</small>\n|- {{party shading/Democratic}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton]]\n| 697\n| 50.40%\n| 23\n| 6\n| 29\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|Bernie Sanders]]\n| 686\n| 49.60%\n| 21\n| 0\n| 21\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Uncommitted\n| \n| \n| \n| 1\n| 1\n|-\n! Total\n! 1,383\n! 100%\n! 44\n! 7\n! 51\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Source: ''[http://iowademocrats.org/2016-iowa-district-convention-results/ Iowa Democrats]''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:12px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"| Iowa State Democratic Convention, June 18, 2016\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Candidate\n! colspan=\"2\" | State delegates\n! colspan=\"3\" | Estimated delegates\n|-\n! style=\"width:70px;\" | Count\n! style=\"width:80px;\" | Percentage\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Pledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Unpledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Total</small>\n|- {{party shading/Democratic}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton]]\n| 714\n| 55.56%\n| 23\n| 6\n| 29\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|Bernie Sanders]]\n| 571\n| 44.44%\n| 21\n| 0\n| 21\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Uncommitted\n| \n| \n| \n| 1\n| 1\n|-\n! Total\n! 1,285\n! 100%\n! 44\n! 7\n! 51\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Source: ''[http://iowademocrats.org/2016-iowa-democratic-party-state-convention-results/#more-15445 Iowa Democrats]''\n|}\n\nFollowing a poor result in the caucuses, [[Martin O'Malley presidential campaign, 2016|Martin O'Malley]] announced he was suspending his campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/02/us/politics/martin-o-malley-ends-presidential-campaign.html|title=Martin O'Malley to Drop Out After Finish in Iowa Vote|last=Parker|first=Ashley|date=2016-02-01|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-06-21}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n[[File:Iowa Democratic caucus results, 2016.svg|thumb|150px|Results of the Iowa Democratic caucus, 2016\n{{legend|#1666cb|Clinton\u201470-80%}}{{legend|#4389e3|Clinton\u201460-70%}}{{legend|#86b6f2|Clinton\u201450-60%}}{{legend|#b9d7ff|Clinton\u2014<50%}}{{legend|Purple|Tie between Clinton and Sanders}}{{legend|#f2b3be|Sanders\u2014<50%}}{{legend|#e27f90|Sanders\u201450-60%}}{{legend|#cc2f4a|Sanders\u201460-70%}}{{legend|#d40000|Sanders\u201470-80%}}]]\n\n\"[O]rganizational issues around the caucus\", including difficulty identifying volunteers to \"oversee individual precinct caucuses,\" contributed to a \"disorganized process that lent itself to chaos and conspiracy theories\" according to ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|title = Iowa Democratic party altered precinct's caucus results during chaotic night|url = https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/05/iowa-democratic-party-altered-precinct-caucus-results-clinton-sanders|newspaper = The Guardian|date = February 5, 2016|access-date = February 6, 2016|issn = 0261-3077|language = en-GB|first = Ben|last = Jacobs}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Both the Sanders and Clinton campaigns have flagged a very small number of concerns for us, and we are looking at them all on a case-by-case basis.|Sam Lau|Iowa Democratic Party}}\n\nAfter initially refusing to review caucus results, Iowa Democratic Party officials did end up \"making updates where discrepancies have been found.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Iowa margin between Clinton, Sanders shifts as errors found|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/05/iowa-margin-between-clinton-sanders-shifts-errors/79877898/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 5, 2016|last = Jacobs|first = Jennifer|date = February 5, 2016|publisher = The USA Today Network}}</ref> With \"doubts about which Democratic candidate actually won the Iowa caucuses,\" there have been \"fresh calls for the party to mirror the simple, secret-ballot method\" the Republicans use. Stated [[Norm Sterzenbach]], former Iowa Democratic Party executive director who oversaw five election cycles: \"It's worth discussing again, but it's not as simple as it sounds.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Uproar could lead to revamping Democratic caucuses|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/06/uproar-could-lead-revamping-democratic-caucuses/79910420/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 7, 2016|date = February 6, 2016|publisher = The USA Today Network|last = Jacobs|first = Jennifer}}</ref> It is said that Clinton won by the thinnest margin in the history of Iowa caucuses.\n\n=== Instances ===\n\nIowa Democrats reported \"discrepancies in caucus results\" and confusion over the math of the delegate-awarding system. In Grinnell Ward 1, 19 delegates were awarded to Sanders and seven to Clinton on caucus night. The Iowa Democratic party later shifted one delegate from Sanders to Clinton, but did not notify the precinct secretary, who \"only discovered that this happened the next day, when checking the precinct results in other parts of the county.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOther reported discrepancies included:\n* the lone caucusgoer in Woodbury County No. 43, who voted for Sanders\u2014but \"final results state\" Clinton won one county delegate and Sanders zero.\n* in Knoxville No. 3, where the count was 58 for Sanders and 52 for Clinton\u2014but official results showed Clinton with five county delegates and Sanders with four.\n* the four delegates in Cedar Rapids No. 9 precinct who split evenly between Sanders and Clinton\u2014but only 131 people signed in at the beginning of the caucus with two separate head counts showing 136 people voted.\nIn Des Moines No. 42, \"after everyone had formed initial groups for their preferred candidate,\" a Clinton supporter addressed O'Malley supporters and undecideds, telling them \"they could stay and realign or leave.\" Some mistakenly believed that meant voting was finished and left early without being counted.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Iowans claim instances when Sanders was shorted delegates|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/06/iowans-claim-instances-when-sanders-shorted-delegates/79902080/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 7, 2016|last = Jacobs|first = Jennifer|publisher = The USA Today Network|date = February 7, 2016}}</ref> In the same precinct, votes were still missing the morning after the caucus. Democrats \"from that neighborhood scrambled to find party officials\" to report that Sanders won by a margin of two delegates over Clinton. This narrowed Clinton's \"excruciatingly close lead\" even further\u2014bringing the tally for \"delegate equivalents\" at that point to Clinton 699.57, Sanders 697.77.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Missing precinct scrambles to report Sanders won|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/02/some-democratic-precinct-results-unaccounted/79682184/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Coin tosses===\n\n''[[The Des Moines Register]]'' reported \"an unknown number\" of county delegates awarded \"after the flip of a coin.\" Sam Lau, a spokesman for the Iowa Democratic Party, said seven coin flips were reported through \"the party's smartphone app\"\u2014but officials who reported county delegate totals via the app \"weren't required to signify if the win was the result of a coin toss.\" Lau said Bernie Sanders won six of these. The paper identified \"six coin flips through social media and one in an interview with a caucus participant\"\u2014with Clinton the apparent winner of six of these seven. Any overlap, or its impact on results, between the coin flips identified by the ''Register'' and those the party confirmed was not known.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2016/02/02/iowa-caucus-coin-flip-count-unknown/79708740/|title=Iowa caucus coin flip count unknown|accessdate = February 3, 2016|publisher = Des Moines Register|date = February 2, 2016|last = Clayworth|first = Jason|last2 = Noble|first2 = Jason|newspaper = The Des Moines Register}}</ref>\n\nAn Iowa Democratic Party official told [[NPR]] there were \"at least a dozen tiebreakers\" decided by a coin toss\u2014 and that \"Sen. Sanders won at least a handful.\"<ref>{{cite web|title = Coin-Toss Fact Check: No, Coin Flips Did Not Win Iowa For Hillary Clinton|url = https://www.npr.org/2016/02/02/465268206/coin-toss-fact-check-no-coin-flips-did-not-win-iowa-for-hillary-clinton|access-date = February 3, 2016|first = Domenico|last = Montanaro|publisher = [[NPR]]|date = February 2, 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160203073439/http://www.npr.org/2016/02/02/465268206/coin-toss-fact-check-no-coin-flips-did-not-win-iowa-for-hillary-clinton|archive-date = February 3, 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Gone unmentioned so far is that even if Clinton won that Miracle Six \u2014 and there were no other coin tosses \u2014 it would make little difference in the outcome. That is, in part, because of the complicated way Iowa Democrats allocate their delegates \u2014 and what was being reported on election night and what wasn't.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Coin-Toss Fact Check: No, Coin Flips Did Not Win Iowa For Hillary Clinton|url = https://www.npr.org/2016/02/02/465268206/coin-toss-fact-check-no-coin-flips-did-not-win-iowa-for-hillary-clinton|website = NPR.org|access-date = February 3, 2016|first = Domenico Montanaro|last = Twitter}}</ref>|Domenico Montanaro|NPR}}\n\n===Review===\n\nSanders' campaign \"launched\" a review of the results of the caucuses, citing as \"complicating factors\" the \"razor-thin margin\", the \"arcane\" caucusing rules, the reporting delays from some precincts, and the reporting technology used. The campaign is rechecking results precinct-by-precinct, reviewing \"math sheets or other paperwork\" precinct chairs used and were supposed to return to party officials\u2014then comparing these with results entered into the party's Microsoft app. Rania Batrice, a Sanders spokeswoman, challenged: \"Let's compare notes. Let's see if they match.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn an editorial, ''The Des Moines Register'' called for an audit of the results, declaring \"What happened Monday night at the Democratic caucuses was a debacle, period.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Editorial: Something smells in the Democratic Party|url = http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/opinion/editorials/caucus/2016/02/03/editorial-something-smells-democratic-party/79777580/|website = Des Moines Register|access-date = February 4, 2016}}</ref> First noting that only two-tenths of a percent separated Sanders and Clinton and \"much larger margins trigger automatic recounts in other states,\" they stated:\n\n<blockquote>Too many accounts have arisen of inconsistent counts, untrained and overwhelmed volunteers, confused voters, cramped precinct locations, a lack of voter registration forms and other problems. Too many of us, including members of the Register editorial board who were observing caucuses, saw opportunities for error amid Monday night's chaos.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>\n\nIn lieu of \"official paper records\" the party had \"declined to provide the campaign\"\u2014which would show individual precinct vote tallies before they were entered into the party's app the night of the caucuses\u2014the Sanders' campaign was contacting each of its own precinct captains to reconstruct caucus results.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Sanders campaign says it was denied paper records of Iowa caucus vote|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/sanders-campaign-says-it-was-denied-paper-records-of-iowa-caucus-vote/2016/02/04/fcdc8f46-cb93-11e5-88ff-e2d1b4289c2f_story.html|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = February 4, 2016|access-date = February 5, 2016|issn = 0190-8286|language = en-US|first = Tom|last = Hamburger}}</ref> Sanders' campaign manager Jeff Weaver said: \"I think everybody has an interest in making it as accurate as possible\", though \"[a]s an empirical matter, we're not likely to ever know what the actual result was\".<ref>{{Cite news|title = Sanders campaign reviewing Iowa caucus totals, says actual result may never be known|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/02/02/sanders-campaign-reviewing-iowa-caucus-totals-says-actual-result-may-never-be-known/|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = February 2, 2016|access-date = February 2, 2016|issn = 0190-8286|language = en-US|first = John|last = Wagner}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Let's not blow this out of proportion. This is not the biggest deal in the world. We think, by the way, based on talking to our precinct captains, we may have at least two more delegates.\"<ref name=\"Jacobs 6.2.16\">{{cite news|last1=Jacobs|first1=Ben|title=Iowa Democratic party altered precinct's caucus results during chaotic night|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/05/iowa-democratic-party-altered-precinct-caucus-results-clinton-sanders|accessdate=February 6, 2016|publisher=The Guardian|date=February 5, 2016}}</ref>|Bernie Sanders}}\n\n== Analysis ==\n[[File:Iowa Caucus Winners - political cartoon by DonkeyHotey (24653531072).jpg|thumb|Iowa Caucus Winners \u2013 political cartoon by DonkeyHotey]]\nDespite a late challenge from insurgent Senator Bernie Sanders of [[Vermont]], whose [[Populism|populist]] economic message resonated with Iowa's [[Progressivism|progressive]] Democratic electorate,{{According to whom|date=February 2017}} Clinton eked out a 0.2-percentage-point victory in the first-in-the-nation caucus, edging out Sanders by only four state delegate equivalents. As ''[[The New York Times]]'' described, Sanders' near-tie with Clinton combined with [[Ted Cruz]]'s [[Iowa Republican caucuses, 2016|Republican]] victory in the caucus demonstrated how the \"2016 campaign has turned to easing the palpable frustrations of a large portion of white working-class Americans who believe that the country no longer works for them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/02/us/iowa-caucus-results.html|title=Fury Shakes the Iowa Caucuses, Boosting Ted Cruz While Slowing Hillary Clinton|last=Barbaro|first=Michael|date=February 2, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to entrance polls, Clinton won the [[Caucasian race|white]] vote by a 49\u201346 margin against Sanders, with white voters comprising 91% of the Iowa electorate. She won [[non-white]] voters more resoundingly, 58\u201334. Sanders won among men, 50\u201344, but Clinton won women, 53-42. Sanders proved his immense strength with [[millennials]] by winning 17\u201329-year-olds 84-14, with Clinton winning [[Old age|senior citizens]], 69\u201326. Clinton won among voters who had a [[high school diploma]] or less, and among those who had a [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate degree]], while Sanders won voters with only a [[Academic degree|college degree]]. Sanders won 53-44 among voters who made an income of less than $50k per year, Clinton won more [[Wealth|affluent]] voters 52-42. In terms of political party affiliation, Clinton won [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] 56-39 but lost [[Independent Party (United States)|Independents]] to Bernie Sanders, 69\u201329.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/election/primaries/polls/ia/Dem|title=2016 Election Center \u2013 Presidential Primaries and Caucuses \u2013 2016 Election Center \u2013 CNNPolitics.com|website=CNN|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nUpon learning she had been awarded the state of Iowa after 1&nbsp;P.M. the following day, Clinton told [[CNN]]'s [[Wolf Blitzer]], \"My luck was not that good last time around, and it was wonderful to win the caucus, to have that experience.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/02/politics/new-hampshire-primary-2016/index.html|title=Hillary Clinton wins Iowa caucuses| first1=Tami | last1=Luhby | first2=Nia-Malika | last2=Henderson |date=February 3, 2016|website=CNN|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2016 Democratic primaries}}\n\n[[Category:2016 United States Democratic presidential primaries by state|Iowa]]\n[[Category:2016 Iowa elections|Democratic primary]]\n[[Category:Iowa Democratic caucuses|2016]]\n", "name_user": "MisterElection2001", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Iowa_Democratic_caucuses"}
{"title_page": "Paparazzi", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Bratislava Bronze Paparazzo.jpg|thumb|Statue of a paparazzo by sculptor Radko Ma\u010duha in [[Bratislava]], Slovakia]]\n[[File:Paparazzo-style photographs (2009 fake).jpg|thumb|Paparazzi style photography]]\n[[File:Barillari rino, Mickey Hargitay, vatussa vitta, Via veneto.jpg|thumb|[[Mickey Hargitay]] assaults the \"king of paparazzi\" [[Rino Barillari]] while a woman hits him with her purse\u2014[[Via Veneto]] 1963]]\n\n[[File:Robbie paparazzi V sign.jpg|thumb|English singer-songwriter and entertainer [[Robbie Williams]] poses for a paparazzo photographer in London in 2000]]\n\n'''Paparazzi''' ({{IPAc-en|US|\u02cc|p|\u0251\u02d0|p|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u0251\u02d0|t|s|i}}, {{IPAc-en|UK|\u02cc|p|\u00e6|p|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u00e6|t|s|i}}; {{IPA-it|papa\u02c8rattsi|lang}}; singular: masculine '''paparazzo''' or feminine '''paparazza''') are [[Freelancer|independent]] [[photographer]]s who take pictures of high-profile people, such as [[actors]], [[Sportsperson|athletes]], [[politician]]s, and other [[celebrity|celebrities]], typically while subjects go about their usual life routines. Paparazzi tend to make a living by selling their photographs to [[mass media|media outlets]] that focus on [[tabloid journalism]] and [[sensationalism]] (such as [[gossip magazine]]s).\n\n== Description ==\nPaparazzi tend to be [[independent contractor]]s, unaffiliated with [[mainstream media]] organizations, and photos taken are usually done so by taking advantage of opportunities when they have sightings of high-profile people they are tracking.<ref name=AJR>{{cite news |url= http://www.ajr.org/Article.asp?id=2325 |title= Is Everyone a Journalist? |work= [[American Journalism Review]] |date= October 1997}}</ref> Some experts have described the behavior of paparazzi as synonymous with [[stalking]], and anti-stalking bills in many countries address the issue by reducing harassment of public figures and celebrities, especially with their [[minor (law)|children]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/24/local/la-me-pc-gov-brown-signs-law-protecting-children-of-public-figures-20130924|title=Gov. Jerry Brown signs law protecting children of public figures|last=McGreevy|first=Patrick|date=September 24, 2013|website=LA Times}}</ref> Some public figures and celebrities have expressed concern at the extent to which paparazzi go to invade their personal space.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://edition.cnn.com/2006/SHOWBIZ/Movies/05/09/sunshine.access/index.html |title= Why Paparazzi Are Wrong |date= March 13, 2006 |publisher= [[CNN]] |accessdate= April 24, 2016}}</ref> The filing and receiving of judicial support for [[restraining order]]s against paparazzi has increased, as have lawsuits with judgments against them.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=M.|first=Locke, Christina|last2=Carnley|first2=Murrhee, Kara|date=2011|title=Is Driving with the Intent to Gather News a Crime? The Chilling Effects of California's Anti-Paparazzi Legislation|url=https://digitalcommons.lmu.edu/elr/vol31/iss2/1/|journal=Loyola of Los Angeles Entertainment Law Review|language=en|volume=31|issue=2}}</ref>\n\n== Famous paparazzi ==\n\n[[Walter Santesso]] portrays Paparazzo in the 1960 film ''[[La Dolce Vita]]'', marking the character as the eponym of the word paparazzi.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dunne|first=Susan|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2008-04-10-altscreenb0410-art-story.html|title=A Movie That Coined A Word|newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=April 10, 2008|accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Ron Galella]] is most known for suing [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]] after the former First Lady ordered her Secret Service agents to destroy Galella\u2019s camera and film following an encounter in New York City's [[Central Park]] in the early 1970s.\n\n== Etymology ==\nA news photographer named Paparazzo (played by [[Walter Santesso]] in the 1960 film ''[[La Dolce Vita]]'' directed by [[Federico Fellini]]) is the [[eponym]] of the word ''paparazzi''.<ref>{{cite encyclopaedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/vocabolario/paparazzo/ |title=Paparazzo |encyclopaedia= [[Treccani]]|language=it}}</ref> {{cn span|In his book ''Word and Phrase'', Robert Hendrickson writes that Fellini took the name from an [[Italian language|Italian]] dialect word that describes a particularly annoying noise, that of a buzzing [[mosquito]].|date=December 2018}} As Fellini said in his interview to ''Time'' magazine, \"''Paparazzo''&nbsp;... suggests to me a buzzing insect, hovering, darting, stinging.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,872287-1,00.html |title= The Press: Paparazzi on the Prowl |work= [[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date= April 14, 1961 |volume=77 |issue=16 |accessdate= October 5, 2009}}</ref> Those versions of the word's origin are sometimes contested. For example, in the [[Abruzzese-Neapolitan|Abruzzo dialect]] spoken by [[Ennio Flaiano]], co-scriptwriter of ''La Dolce Vita'', the term ''paparazzo'' refers to the local clam, ''[[Venerupis decussata]]'', and is also used as a metaphor for the shutter of a camera lens.\n\nFurther, in an interview with Fellini's screenwriter Flaiano, he said the name came from the book ''Sulla riva dello Jonio'' (1957),<ref>{{cite book |last=Gissing |first=George Robert |authorlink=George Gissing |title=Sulla riva dello Ionio. Appunti di viaggio nell'Italia meridionale |url=https://books.google.com/?id=3-0QcgAACAAJ |others=transl. by [[Margherita Guidacci]] |year=1957 |publisher=Capelli |location=[[Bologna]]|language=it}}</ref> a translation by Italian poet [[Margherita Guidacci]] of ''By the Ionian Sea'',<ref>{{cite book |last=Gissing |first=George |title=By the Ionian Sea. Notes of a Ramble in Southern Italy |url=https://books.google.com/?id=CjrJ6aUWOrwC&printsec=frontcover |year=2004 |origyear=1901 |publisher=[[Signal Books]] |location=[[Oxford]] |edition=illustrated, reprint, revised |isbn=978-1-90266967-0 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=CjrJ6aUWOrwC&pg=PA145 145]}}</ref> a 1901 travel narrative in southern Italy by Victorian writer [[George Gissing]]. He further states that either Fellini or Flaiano opened the book at random, saw the name of a restaurant owner, Coriolano Paparazzo, and decided to use it for the photographer. This story is further documented by a variety of Gissing scholars<ref>{{cite book |last=Coustillas |first=Pierre |authorlink=Pierre Coustillas |chapter=Gissing and the Paparazzi (pp. 256\u2013266) |chapter-url= https://books.google.com/books?id=uxDlXxc_8TUC&pg=PA256 |editor-first= Francesco |editor-last=Badolato |title=George Gissing, romanziere del tardo periodo vittoriano |year=2005 |publisher=Rubbettino Editore |location=[[Soveria Mannelli]] |isbn=978-8-84981193-3 }}</ref> and in the book ''A Sweet and Glorious Land. Revisiting the Ionian Sea''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Keahey |first=John |title=A Sweet and Glorious Land. Revisiting the Ionian Sea |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-w-jAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |year=2014 |origyear=[https://books.google.com/books?id=j2zOAwAAQBAJ 2000] |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] |location=London |isbn=978-1-46687603-3 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=-w-jAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT184 184]}}</ref>\nBy the late 1960s, the word, usually in the Italian plural form ''paparazzi'', had entered English as a generic term for intrusive photographers.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.word-origins.com/definition/paparazzi.html |work= Word Origins and History |title= Paparazzi |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101220005135/http://www.word-origins.com/definition/paparazzi.html |archivedate= December 20, 2010 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> A person who has been photographed by the paparazzi is said to have been \"papped\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/pap|title=pap - definition of pap in English {{!}} Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries {{!}} English|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== In other languages ===\nA [[transliteration]] of ''paparazzi'' is used in several languages that do not use the Latin alphabet, including [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Thai language|Thai]] and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]. [[Chinese language|Chinese]] uses {{linktext|\u72d7|\u4ed4|\u968a}}, meaning \"puppy squad\". [[Khmer language|Khmer]] uses {{lang|km|\u17a2\u17d2\u1793\u1780\u1794\u17d2\u179a\u1798\u17b6\u1789\u17cb\u179a\u17bc\u1794}} (anak bramanh roub).\n\n== Legality ==\nDue to the reputation of paparazzi as a nuisance, several states and countries restrict their activities by passing laws and [[curfew]]s,{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} and by staging events in which paparazzi are specifically not allowed to take photographs.<ref>{{cite web |title= AB 2479 Bill Analysis |first= Ellen M. |last= Corbett |url= http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/09-10/bill/asm/ab_2451-2500/ab_2479_cfa_20100628_125856_sen_comm.html |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= SB 465 Summary |url= http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2013/Bills/SB465_.HTM |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= How Princess Diana Changed the Way Paparazzi Pursue Kate Middleton |first= Danna |last= Harman |url= http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2011/0429/How-Princess-Diana-changed-the-way-paparazzi-pursue-Kate-Middleton |work= [[Christian Science Monitor]] |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= French Paparazzi Laws Favor Celebrities: Jolie, Pitt Latest Couple to Benefit |first= Angela |last= Doland |url= http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2004470054_brangelina11.html |work= [[Seattle Times]] |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref> In the United States, celebrity news organizations are protected by the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]].<ref>{{cite journal |title= Taking a Shot at Paparazzi |last= Lowry |first= Brian |date= August 6, 2013 |journal= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |volume= 320 |issue= 17 |pages= |id= {{ProQuest|1429233078}} }}</ref>\n\nTo protect the children of celebrities, California passed a new bill in September 2013. The purpose of the bill is to stop paparazzi from taking pictures of children in a [[Harassment|harassing]] manner, regardless of who their parents are. This law increased the penalty on harassment and the penalty for harassment of children.<ref>{{cite news |last= McGreevy |first= Patrick |title= Gov. Brown Signs Bills Aimed at Paparazzi, Family Leave and Quakes |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/24/local/la-me-brown-bills-paparazzi-20130925 |access-date= April 19, 2014 |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date= September 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Injunctions ===\n[[File:Paparazzi by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|right|A group of [[Photojournalism|photojournalists]] often known as paparazzi]]\n\nIn 1972, paparazzo photographer [[Ron Galella]] sued [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]] after the former First Lady ordered her Secret Service agents to destroy Galella's camera and film following an encounter in New York City's [[Central Park]]. Kennedy counter-sued claiming harassment. The trial lasted three weeks and became a groundbreaking case regarding photojournalism and the role of paparazzi. In ''Galella v. Onassis'', Kennedy obtained a restraining order to keep Galella {{convert|150|ft|m}} away from her and her children. The restriction later was dropped to {{convert|25|ft|m}}. The trial is a focal point in ''[[Smash His Camera]]'', a 2010 documentary film by director [[Leon Gast]].\n\nIn 1997, [[Diana, Princess of Wales]] and [[Dodi Fayed]] were [[Death of Diana, Princess of Wales|killed in a limousine crash]] as their driver was speeding, trying to escape paparazzi.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.express.co.uk/news/royal/504736/Princess-Diana-Security-DIY-Car-Crash-Paris |title= Policeman who Spoke to Dying Princess Diana Blasts 'DIY' Security who Failed to Stop Crash |access-date= November 11, 2014 |last1= Allen |first1= Peter |date= August 29, 2014 |work= Express |location= London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/31/newsid_2510000/2510615.stm |publisher= [[BBC]] |title= 1997: Princess Diana Dies in Paris Crash |access-date= November 11, 2014}}</ref> An inquest jury investigated the involvement of paparazzi in the incident, and although several paparazzi were taken into custody, no one was convicted.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}<!-- That several paparazzi were taken into custody probably isn't common knowledge, so needs a citation, although the facts that paparazzi were investigated and none were convicted probably is common knowledge and therefore doesn't need a citation. --> The official inquests into the accident attributed the causes to the speed and manner of driving of the Mercedes, as well as the following vehicles, and the impairment of the judgment of the Mercedes driver, [[Henri Paul]], through alcohol.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottbaker_inquests.gov.uk/evidence/docs/inquisition_diana.pdf |title=Jury verdict - Inquisition forms: Princess Diana of Wales |website=Coroner's Inquests into the Deaths of Diana, Princess of Wales and Mr Dodi Al Fayed |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090607230257/http://www.scottbaker-inquests.gov.uk/evidence/docs/inquisition_diana.pdf |archive-date=June 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the ''[[Oriental Daily News]]'' of Hong Kong was found guilty of \"scandalizing the court\", an extremely rare law that the newspaper's conduct would undermine confidence in the administration of justice.<ref name=\"WorldLII\">{{cite court | |litigants= Wong Yeung Ng v. Secretary for Justice |reporter= ICHRL |opinion= 12 |date=  February 9, 1999 |url= http://www.worldlii.org/int/cases/ICHRL/1999/12.html |access-date=August 20, 2006 }}</ref> The charge was brought after the newspaper had published abusive articles challenging the judiciary's integrity and accusing it of [[bias]] in a lawsuit the paper had instigated over a photo of a pregnant [[Faye Wong]]. The paper had also arranged for a \"dog team\" (slang for paparazzi in the Chinese language) to track a judge for 72 hours, to provide the judge with first-hand experience of what paparazzi do.<ref name=\"ODN\">{{cite journal |first= Tim |last= Hamlett |date= July\u2013December 2011 |title= Scandalising the Scumbags: The Secretary for Justice vs the Oriental Press Group |url= http://www.uow.edu.au/crearts/journalism/APME/contents11/TimHamlett.pdf |journal= Asia Pacific Media Educator |volume= |issue= 11 |pages= 20\u201333 |access-date= August 20, 2006 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060518072905/http://www.uow.edu.au/crearts/journalism/APME/contents11/TimHamlett.pdf |archive-date= May 18, 2006}}</ref>\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's Style & Design special issue in 2005 ran a story entitled \"Shooting Star\", in which Mel Bouzad, one of the top paparazzi in Los Angeles at the time, claimed to have made US$150,000 for a picture of [[Ben Affleck]] and [[Jennifer Lopez]] in Georgia after their breakup. \"If I get a picture of [[Britney Spears|Britney]] and her baby,\" Bouzad claimed, \"I'll be able to buy a house in those hills (above [[Sunset Boulevard]]).\"<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news |title= Shooting Stars |url= http://www.time.com/time/2005/style/091305/shooting_stars_paparazz39a.html |access-date= June 16, 2006 |work= Time |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20051226032035/http://www.time.com/time/2005/style/091305/shooting_stars_paparazz39a.html |archive-date= December 26, 2005}}</ref> ''Paparazzi'' author Peter Howe told ''Time'' that \"celebrities need a higher level of exposure than the rest of us so it is a two-way street. The celebrities manipulate.\"\n\nIn 2006, [[Daniella Cicarelli]] went through a scandal when a paparazzo caught video footage of her having sex with her boyfriend on a beach in Spain, which was posted on [[YouTube]].<ref>[http://oglobo.globo.com/cultura/mat/2006/09/28/285875345.asp Justi\u00e7a mant\u00e9m liminar que obriga sites a tirar v\u00eddeo de Cicarelli com namorado do ar] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308025739/http://oglobo.globo.com/cultura/mat/2006/09/28/285875345.asp |date=March 8, 2008 }}</ref> After fighting in the court, it was decided in her favor, causing YouTube to be blocked in Brazil. This caused major havoc among Brazilians, including threatening a [[boycott]] against [[MTV Brasil]] unless Cicarelli was fired from that company.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} The block only lasted a few days, and Cicarelli was not dismissed. The legal action backfired as the court decided she had no [[expectation of privacy]] by having sex in a public location.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nThe [[E!]] network program ''[[Celebrities Uncensored]]'' used often-confrontational footage of celebrities made by paparazzi.\n\nFollowing the publication of photographs showing [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]] sunbathing whilst topless at her husband's cousin's ([[David Armstrong-Jones, Viscount Linley|Viscount Linley]]'s) holiday home in France, it was announced on September 14, 2012, that the Royal couple were to launch legal action against the French edition of [[Closer (magazine)|''Closer'']] magazine. It was the first time that a senior royal has sued in a court outside the UK. The reason cited for the legal action is that the Duchess had a right of privacy whilst at the home\u2014the magazine responded that the pictures had been taken from the public highway. The injunction was granted September 18, 2012 and the publishers of the magazine were ordered not to publish the photographs in France and not to sell the images. The publishers were also ordered to hand over the original material of the published pictures under threat of a \u20ac10,000 fine for every day delay in doing so.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mrpaparazzi.com |title= mrpaparazzi.com |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080216110716/http://www.mrpaparazzi.com/ |archive-date= February 16, 2008 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, [[Sienna Miller]], [[Amy Winehouse]], and [[Lily Allen]] won injunctions that prevent the paparazzi from following them and gathering outside their houses. Miller was awarded \u00a353,000.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/may/04/celebrities-paparazzi |title= Have Celebrities Finally Snapped? |newspaper= The Guardian |location= London |date= May 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, rapper [[Kanye West]], facing assault charges for attacking a photojournalist, said he would fight to get the law changed so celebrities can profit from the paparazzi's work.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Kanye-West-demands-money-from-paparazzi/tabid/418/articleID/314523/Default.aspx |title= Kanye West Demands Money from Paparazzi |publisher= 3 News NZ |date= September 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/kanye-west-paparazzi-should-pay-2296723 |title= Kanye West: 'The Paparazzi Should Pay Me' |work= The Mirror |location= London |date= September 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Wiktionary-inline}}\n* [https://www.aenigma-images.com/2018/03/the-paparazzi/ The paparazzi] at [https://www.aenigma-images.com/ aenigma]\n* [https://eventspaparazzi.co.uk/ Paparazzi] at [https://eventspaparazzi.co.uk/fake-events-paparazzi-photography/]\n\n{{Federico Fellini|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Photojournalism]]\n[[Category:Journalism ethics]]\n[[Category:Criticism of journalism]]\n[[Category:Celebrity]]\n[[Category:Media bias controversies]]\n[[Category:Federico Fellini]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1960s]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n[[File:Bratislava Bronze Paparazzo.jpg|thumb|Statue of a paparazzo by sculptor Radko Ma\u010duha in [[Bratislava]], Slovakia]]\n[[File:Paparazzo-style photographs (2009 fake).jpg|thumb|Paparazzi style photography]]\n[[File:Barillari rino, Mickey Hargitay, vatussa vitta, Via veneto.jpg|thumb|[[Mickey Hargitay]] assaults the \"king of paparazzi\" [[Rino Barillari]] while a woman hits him with her purse\u2014[[Via Veneto]] 1963]]\n\n[[File:Robbie paparazzi V sign.jpg|thumb|English singer-songwriter and entertainer [[Robbie Williams]] poses for a paparazzo photographer in London in 2000]]\n\n'''Paparazzi''' ({{IPAc-en|US|\u02cc|p|\u0251\u02d0|p|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u0251\u02d0|t|s|i}}, {{IPAc-en|UK|\u02cc|p|\u00e6|p|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u00e6|t|s|i}}; {{IPA-it|papa\u02c8rattsi|lang}}; singular: masculine '''paparazzo''' or feminine '''paparazza''') are [[Freelancer|independent]] [[photographer]]s who take pictures of high-profile people, such as [[actors]], [[Sportsperson|athletes]], [[politician]]s, and other [[celebrity|celebrities]], typically while subjects go about their usual life routines. Paparazzi tend to make a living by selling their photographs to [[mass media|media outlets]] that focus on [[tabloid journalism]] and [[sensationalism]] (such as [[gossip magazine]]s).\n\n== Description ==\nPaparazzi tend to be [[independent contractor]]s, unaffiliated with [[mainstream media]] organizations, and photos taken are usually done so by taking advantage of opportunities when they have sightings of high-profile people they are tracking.<ref name=AJR>{{cite news |url= http://www.ajr.org/Article.asp?id=2325 |title= Is Everyone a Journalist? |work= [[American Journalism Review]] |date= October 1997}}</ref> Some experts have described the behavior of paparazzi as synonymous with [[stalking]], and anti-stalking bills in many countries address the issue by reducing harassment of public figures and celebrities, especially with their [[minor (law)|children]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/24/local/la-me-pc-gov-brown-signs-law-protecting-children-of-public-figures-20130924|title=Gov. Jerry Brown signs law protecting children of public figures|last=McGreevy|first=Patrick|date=September 24, 2013|website=LA Times}}</ref> Some public figures and celebrities have expressed concern at the extent to which paparazzi go to invade their personal space.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://edition.cnn.com/2006/SHOWBIZ/Movies/05/09/sunshine.access/index.html |title= Why Paparazzi Are Wrong |date= March 13, 2006 |publisher= [[CNN]] |accessdate= April 24, 2016}}</ref> The filing and receiving of judicial support for [[restraining order]]s against paparazzi has increased, as have lawsuits with judgments against them.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=M.|first=Locke, Christina|last2=Carnley|first2=Murrhee, Kara|date=2011|title=Is Driving with the Intent to Gather News a Crime? The Chilling Effects of California's Anti-Paparazzi Legislation|url=https://digitalcommons.lmu.edu/elr/vol31/iss2/1/|journal=Loyola of Los Angeles Entertainment Law Review|language=en|volume=31|issue=2}}</ref>\n\n== Famous paparazzi ==\n\n[[Walter Santesso]] portrays Paparazzo in the 1960 film ''[[La Dolce Vita]]'', marking the character as the eponym of the word paparazzi.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dunne|first=Susan|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2008-04-10-altscreenb0410-art-story.html|title=A Movie That Coined A Word|newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=April 10, 2008|accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Ron Galella]] is most known for suing [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]] after the former First Lady ordered her Secret Service agents to destroy Galella\u2019s camera and film following an encounter in New York City's [[Central Park]] in the early 1970s.\n\n== Etymology ==\nA news photographer named Paparazzo (played by [[Walter Santesso]] in the 1960 film ''[[La Dolce Vita]]'' directed by [[Federico Fellini]]) is the [[eponym]] of the word ''paparazzi''.<ref>{{cite encyclopaedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/vocabolario/paparazzo/ |title=Paparazzo |encyclopaedia= [[Treccani]]|language=it}}</ref> {{cn span|In his book ''Word and Phrase'', Robert Hendrickson writes that Fellini took the name from an [[Italian language|Italian]] dialect word that describes a particularly annoying noise, that of a buzzing [[mosquito]].|date=December 2018}} As Fellini said in his interview to ''Time'' magazine, \"''Paparazzo''&nbsp;... suggests to me a buzzing insect, hovering, darting, stinging.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,872287-1,00.html |title= The Press: Paparazzi on the Prowl |work= [[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date= April 14, 1961 |volume=77 |issue=16 |accessdate= October 5, 2009}}</ref> Those versions of the word's origin are sometimes contested. For example, in the [[Abruzzese-Neapolitan|Abruzzo dialect]] spoken by [[Ennio Flaiano]], co-scriptwriter of ''La Dolce Vita'', the term ''paparazzo'' refers to the local clam, ''[[Venerupis decussata]]'', and is also used as a metaphor for the shutter of a camera lens.\n\nFurther, in an interview with Fellini's screenwriter Flaiano, he said the name came from the book ''Sulla riva dello Jonio'' (1957),<ref>{{cite book |last=Gissing |first=George Robert |authorlink=George Gissing |title=Sulla riva dello Ionio. Appunti di viaggio nell'Italia meridionale |url=https://books.google.com/?id=3-0QcgAACAAJ |others=transl. by [[Margherita Guidacci]] |year=1957 |publisher=Capelli |location=[[Bologna]]|language=it}}</ref> a translation by Italian poet [[Margherita Guidacci]] of ''By the Ionian Sea'',<ref>{{cite book |last=Gissing |first=George |title=By the Ionian Sea. Notes of a Ramble in Southern Italy |url=https://books.google.com/?id=CjrJ6aUWOrwC&printsec=frontcover |year=2004 |origyear=1901 |publisher=[[Signal Books]] |location=[[Oxford]] |edition=illustrated, reprint, revised |isbn=978-1-90266967-0 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=CjrJ6aUWOrwC&pg=PA145 145]}}</ref> a 1901 travel narrative in southern Italy by Victorian writer [[George Gissing]]. He further states that either Fellini or Flaiano opened the book at random, saw the name of a restaurant owner, Coriolano Paparazzo, and decided to use it for the photographer. This story is further documented by a variety of Gissing scholars<ref>{{cite book |last=Coustillas |first=Pierre |authorlink=Pierre Coustillas |chapter=Gissing and the Paparazzi (pp. 256\u2013266) |chapter-url= https://books.google.com/books?id=uxDlXxc_8TUC&pg=PA256 |editor-first= Francesco |editor-last=Badolato |title=George Gissing, romanziere del tardo periodo vittoriano |year=2005 |publisher=Rubbettino Editore |location=[[Soveria Mannelli]] |isbn=978-8-84981193-3 }}</ref> and in the book ''A Sweet and Glorious Land. Revisiting the Ionian Sea''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Keahey |first=John |title=A Sweet and Glorious Land. Revisiting the Ionian Sea |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-w-jAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |year=2014 |origyear=[https://books.google.com/books?id=j2zOAwAAQBAJ 2000] |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] |location=London |isbn=978-1-46687603-3 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=-w-jAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT184 184]}}</ref>\nBy the late 1960s, the word, usually in the Italian plural form ''paparazzi'', had entered English as a generic term for intrusive photographers.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.word-origins.com/definition/paparazzi.html |work= Word Origins and History |title= Paparazzi |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101220005135/http://www.word-origins.com/definition/paparazzi.html |archivedate= December 20, 2010 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> A person who has been photographed by the paparazzi is said to have been \"papped\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/pap|title=pap - definition of pap in English {{!}} Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries {{!}} English|accessdate=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n\n=== In other languages ===\nA [[transliteration]] of ''paparazzi'' is used in several languages that do not use the Latin alphabet, including [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Thai language|Thai]] and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]. [[Chinese language|Chinese]] uses {{linktext|\u72d7|\u4ed4|\u968a}}, meaning \"puppy squad\". [[Khmer language|Khmer]] uses {{lang|km|\u17a2\u17d2\u1793\u1780\u1794\u17d2\u179a\u1798\u17b6\u1789\u17cb\u179a\u17bc\u1794}} (anak bramanh roub).\n\n== Legality ==\nDue to the reputation of paparazzi as a nuisance, several states and countries restrict their activities by passing laws and [[curfew]]s,{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} and by staging events in which paparazzi are specifically not allowed to take photographs.<ref>{{cite web |title= AB 2479 Bill Analysis |first= Ellen M. |last= Corbett |url= http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/09-10/bill/asm/ab_2451-2500/ab_2479_cfa_20100628_125856_sen_comm.html |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= SB 465 Summary |url= http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2013/Bills/SB465_.HTM |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= How Princess Diana Changed the Way Paparazzi Pursue Kate Middleton |first= Danna |last= Harman |url= http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2011/0429/How-Princess-Diana-changed-the-way-paparazzi-pursue-Kate-Middleton |work= [[Christian Science Monitor]] |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= French Paparazzi Laws Favor Celebrities: Jolie, Pitt Latest Couple to Benefit |first= Angela |last= Doland |url= http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2004470054_brangelina11.html |work= [[Seattle Times]] |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref> In the United States, celebrity news organizations are protected by the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]].<ref>{{cite journal |title= Taking a Shot at Paparazzi |last= Lowry |first= Brian |date= August 6, 2013 |journal= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |volume= 320 |issue= 17 |pages= |id= {{ProQuest|1429233078}} }}</ref>\n\nTo protect the children of celebrities, California passed a new bill in September 2013. The purpose of the bill is to stop paparazzi from taking pictures of children in a [[Harassment|harassing]] manner, regardless of who their parents are. This law increased the penalty on harassment and the penalty for harassment of children.<ref>{{cite news |last= McGreevy |first= Patrick |title= Gov. Brown Signs Bills Aimed at Paparazzi, Family Leave and Quakes |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/24/local/la-me-brown-bills-paparazzi-20130925 |access-date= April 19, 2014 |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date= September 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Injunctions ===\n[[File:Paparazzi by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|right|A group of [[Photojournalism|photojournalists]] often known as paparazzi]]\n\nIn 1972, paparazzo photographer [[Ron Galella]] sued [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]] after the former First Lady ordered her Secret Service agents to destroy Galella's camera and film following an encounter in New York City's [[Central Park]]. Kennedy counter-sued claiming harassment. The trial lasted three weeks and became a groundbreaking case regarding photojournalism and the role of paparazzi. In ''Galella v. Onassis'', Kennedy obtained a restraining order to keep Galella {{convert|150|ft|m}} away from her and her children. The restriction later was dropped to {{convert|25|ft|m}}. The trial is a focal point in ''[[Smash His Camera]]'', a 2010 documentary film by director [[Leon Gast]].\n\nIn 1997, [[Diana, Princess of Wales]] and [[Dodi Fayed]] were [[Death of Diana, Princess of Wales|killed in a limousine crash]] as their driver was speeding, trying to escape paparazzi.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.express.co.uk/news/royal/504736/Princess-Diana-Security-DIY-Car-Crash-Paris |title= Policeman who Spoke to Dying Princess Diana Blasts 'DIY' Security who Failed to Stop Crash |access-date= November 11, 2014 |last1= Allen |first1= Peter |date= August 29, 2014 |work= Express |location= London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/31/newsid_2510000/2510615.stm |publisher= [[BBC]] |title= 1997: Princess Diana Dies in Paris Crash |access-date= November 11, 2014}}</ref> An inquest jury investigated the involvement of paparazzi in the incident, and although several paparazzi were taken into custody, no one was convicted.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}<!-- That several paparazzi were taken into custody probably isn't common knowledge, so needs a citation, although the facts that paparazzi were investigated and none were convicted probably is common knowledge and therefore doesn't need a citation. --> The official inquests into the accident attributed the causes to the speed and manner of driving of the Mercedes, as well as the following vehicles, and the impairment of the judgment of the Mercedes driver, [[Henri Paul]], through alcohol.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottbaker_inquests.gov.uk/evidence/docs/inquisition_diana.pdf |title=Jury verdict - Inquisition forms: Princess Diana of Wales |website=Coroner's Inquests into the Deaths of Diana, Princess of Wales and Mr Dodi Al Fayed |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090607230257/http://www.scottbaker-inquests.gov.uk/evidence/docs/inquisition_diana.pdf |archive-date=June 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the ''[[Oriental Daily News]]'' of Hong Kong was found guilty of \"scandalizing the court\", an extremely rare law that the newspaper's conduct would undermine confidence in the administration of justice.<ref name=\"WorldLII\">{{cite court | |litigants= Wong Yeung Ng v. Secretary for Justice |reporter= ICHRL |opinion= 12 |date=  February 9, 1999 |url= http://www.worldlii.org/int/cases/ICHRL/1999/12.html |access-date=August 20, 2006 }}</ref> The charge was brought after the newspaper had published abusive articles challenging the judiciary's integrity and accusing it of [[bias]] in a lawsuit the paper had instigated over a photo of a pregnant [[Faye Wong]]. The paper had also arranged for a \"dog team\" (slang for paparazzi in the Chinese language) to track a judge for 72 hours, to provide the judge with first-hand experience of what paparazzi do.<ref name=\"ODN\">{{cite journal |first= Tim |last= Hamlett |date= July\u2013December 2011 |title= Scandalising the Scumbags: The Secretary for Justice vs the Oriental Press Group |url= http://www.uow.edu.au/crearts/journalism/APME/contents11/TimHamlett.pdf |journal= Asia Pacific Media Educator |volume= |issue= 11 |pages= 20\u201333 |access-date= August 20, 2006 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060518072905/http://www.uow.edu.au/crearts/journalism/APME/contents11/TimHamlett.pdf |archive-date= May 18, 2006}}</ref>\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's Style & Design special issue in 2005 ran a story entitled \"Shooting Star\", in which Mel Bouzad, one of the top paparazzi in Los Angeles at the time, claimed to have made US$150,000 for a picture of [[Ben Affleck]] and [[Jennifer Lopez]] in Georgia after their breakup. \"If I get a picture of [[Britney Spears|Britney]] and her baby,\" Bouzad claimed, \"I'll be able to buy a house in those hills (above [[Sunset Boulevard]]).\"<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news |title= Shooting Stars |url= http://www.time.com/time/2005/style/091305/shooting_stars_paparazz39a.html |access-date= June 16, 2006 |work= Time |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20051226032035/http://www.time.com/time/2005/style/091305/shooting_stars_paparazz39a.html |archive-date= December 26, 2005}}</ref> ''Paparazzi'' author Peter Howe told ''Time'' that \"celebrities need a higher level of exposure than the rest of us so it is a two-way street. The celebrities manipulate.\"\n\nIn 2006, [[Daniella Cicarelli]] went through a scandal when a paparazzo caught video footage of her having sex with her boyfriend on a beach in Spain, which was posted on [[YouTube]].<ref>[http://oglobo.globo.com/cultura/mat/2006/09/28/285875345.asp Justi\u00e7a mant\u00e9m liminar que obriga sites a tirar v\u00eddeo de Cicarelli com namorado do ar] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308025739/http://oglobo.globo.com/cultura/mat/2006/09/28/285875345.asp |date=March 8, 2008 }}</ref> After fighting in the court, it was decided in her favor, causing YouTube to be blocked in Brazil. This caused major havoc among Brazilians, including threatening a [[boycott]] against [[MTV Brasil]] unless Cicarelli was fired from that company.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} The block only lasted a few days, and Cicarelli was not dismissed. The legal action backfired as the court decided she had no [[expectation of privacy]] by having sex in a public location.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nThe [[E!]] network program ''[[Celebrities Uncensored]]'' used often-confrontational footage of celebrities made by paparazzi.\n\nFollowing the publication of photographs showing [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]] sunbathing whilst topless at her husband's cousin's ([[David Armstrong-Jones, Viscount Linley|Viscount Linley]]'s) holiday home in France, it was announced on September 14, 2012, that the Royal couple were to launch legal action against the French edition of [[Closer (magazine)|''Closer'']] magazine. It was the first time that a senior royal has sued in a court outside the UK. The reason cited for the legal action is that the Duchess had a right of privacy whilst at the home\u2014the magazine responded that the pictures had been taken from the public highway. The injunction was granted September 18, 2012 and the publishers of the magazine were ordered not to publish the photographs in France and not to sell the images. The publishers were also ordered to hand over the original material of the published pictures under threat of a \u20ac10,000 fine for every day delay in doing so.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mrpaparazzi.com |title= mrpaparazzi.com |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080216110716/http://www.mrpaparazzi.com/ |archive-date= February 16, 2008 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, [[Sienna Miller]], [[Amy Winehouse]], and [[Lily Allen]] won injunctions that prevent the paparazzi from following them and gathering outside their houses. Miller was awarded \u00a353,000.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/may/04/celebrities-paparazzi |title= Have Celebrities Finally Snapped? |newspaper= The Guardian |location= London |date= May 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, rapper [[Kanye West]], facing assault charges for attacking a photojournalist, said he would fight to get the law changed so celebrities can profit from the paparazzi's work.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Kanye-West-demands-money-from-paparazzi/tabid/418/articleID/314523/Default.aspx |title= Kanye West Demands Money from Paparazzi |publisher= 3 News NZ |date= September 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/kanye-west-paparazzi-should-pay-2296723 |title= Kanye West: 'The Paparazzi Should Pay Me' |work= The Mirror |location= London |date= September 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Wiktionary-inline}}\n* [https://www.aenigma-images.com/2018/03/the-paparazzi/ The paparazzi] at [https://www.aenigma-images.com/ aenigma]\n* [https://eventspaparazzi.co.uk/ Paparazzi] at [https://eventspaparazzi.co.uk/fake-events-paparazzi-photography/]\n\n{{Federico Fellini|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Photojournalism]]\n[[Category:Journalism ethics]]\n[[Category:Criticism of journalism]]\n[[Category:Celebrity]]\n[[Category:Media bias controversies]]\n[[Category:Federico Fellini]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1960s]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paparazzi"}
