{"title_page": "Lucretia Lombard", "text_new": "{{short description|1923 film by Jack Conway}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Lucretia Lombard\n| image          = Lucretia Lombard 1923 poster.jpg\n| caption        = Movie poster\n| director       = [[Jack Conway (filmmaker)|Jack Conway]]\n| producer       = [[Harry Rapf]]\n| writer         = Scenario:<br>[[Bertram Milhauser]]<br>[[Sada Cowan]] \n| based on       = {{basedon|''Lucretia Lombard''|[[Kathleen Norris]]}}\n| starring       = [[Irene Rich]]<br>[[Monte Blue]]<br>[[Norma Shearer]]\n| cinematography = \n| editing        =\n| studio         = [[Warner Bros.]]\n| distributor    = Warner Bros.\n| released       = {{film date|1923|12|08|limited release}}\n| runtime        = 7 [[reel#Motion picture terminology|reels]]\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n| budget         =$128,000<ref name=\"warners\">Warner Bros financial information in The William Shaefer Ledger. See Appendix 1, Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television, (1995) 15:sup1, 1-31 p 2 DOI: 10.1080/01439689508604551</ref>\n| gross          =$385,000<ref name=\"warners\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Lucretia Lombard''''', also known as '''''Flaming Passion''''', is a 1923 American [[silent film|silent]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Jack Conway (filmmaker)|Jack Conway]] and produced and distributed by [[Warner Bros.]] Based upon the 1922 novel of the same name by [[Kathleen Norris]], it stars [[Irene Rich]], [[Monte Blue]] and a young [[Norma Shearer]], just prior to her signing with [[MGM]].<ref>[http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=10478 The AFI Catalog of Feature Films:''Lucretia Lombard'']</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/L/LucretiaLombard1923.html Progressive Silent Film List: ''Lucretia Lombard''] at silentera.com</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Irene Rich]] as Lucretia Lombard\n*[[Monte Blue]] as Stephen Winship\n*[[Marc McDermott]] as Sir Allen Lombard\n*[[Norma Shearer]] as Mimi\n*[[Alec B. Francis]] as Judge Winship\n*John Roche as Fred Winship\n*[[Lucy Beaumont (actress)|Lucy Beaumont]] as Mrs. Winship\n*[[Otto Hoffman]] as Sandy, Lombard's servant\n*[[Florence Lawrence]]\n\n==Box office==\nAccording to Warner Bros records the film earned $348,000 domestically and $37,000 foreign.<ref name=\"warners\"/>\n\n==Preservation status==\nThis film still survives at [[George Eastman House]] and [[Pacific Film Archive]].<ref>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.mbrs.sfdb.1458/default.html The Library of Congress American Silent Feature Film Survival Catalog: ''Lucretia Lombard'']</ref> It was transferred onto 16mm film by [[Associated Artists Productions]]<ref>[https://archive.org/details/mediahistory&tab=collection?and%5B%5D=subject%3A%22Motion%20pictures%20--%20Catalogues%22 1957 Movies from AAP Warner Bros Features & Cartoons, Sales Book Directed at TV]</ref> in the 1950s and shown on television.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Lucretia Lombard}}\n*{{IMDb title|0014229}}\n*{{allmovie|100669|Synopsis}}\n\n{{Jack Conway}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lucretia Lombard}}\n[[Category:1923 films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jack Conway]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Harry Rapf]]\n[[Category:1920s drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Surviving American silent films]]\n\n\n{{1920s-silent-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1923 film by Jack Conway}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Lucretia Lombard\n| image          = Lucretia Lombard 1923 poster.jpg\n| caption        = Movie poster\n| director       = [[Jack Conway (filmmaker)|Jack Conway]]\n| producer       = [[Harry Rapf]]\n| writer         = Scenario:<br>[[Bertram Milhauser]]<br>[[Sada Cowan]] \n| based on       = {{basedon|''Lucretia Lombard''|[[Kathleen Norris]]}}\n| starring       = [[Irene Rich]]<br>[[Monte Blue]]<br>[[Norma Shearer]]\n| cinematography = \n| editing        =\n| studio         = [[Warner Bros.]]\n| distributor    = Warner Bros.\n| released       = {{film date|1923|12|08|limited release}}\n| runtime        = 7 [[reel#Motion picture terminology|reels]]\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n| budget         =$128,000<ref name=\"warners\">Warner Bros financial information in The William Shaefer Ledger. See Appendix 1, Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television, (1995) 15:sup1, 1-31 p 2 DOI: 10.1080/01439689508604551</ref>\n| gross          =$385,000<ref name=\"warners\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Lucretia Lombard''''', also known as '''''Flaming Passion''''', is a 1923 American [[silent film|silent]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Jack Conway (filmmaker)|Jack Conway]] and produced and distributed by [[Warner Bros.]] Based upon the 1922 novel of the same name by [[Kathleen Norris]], it stars [[Irene Rich]], [[Monte Blue]] and a young [[Norma Shearer]], just prior to her signing with [[MGM]].<ref>[http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=10478 The AFI Catalog of Feature Films:''Lucretia Lombard'']</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/L/LucretiaLombard1923.html Progressive Silent Film List: ''Lucretia Lombard''] at silentera.com</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Irene Rich]] as Lucretia Lombard\n*[[Monte Blue]] as Stephen Winship\n*[[Marc McDermott]] as Sir Allen Lombard\n*[[Norma Shearer]] as Mimi\n*[[Alec B. Francis]] as Judge Winship\n*John Roche as Fred Winship\n*[[Lucy Beaumont (actress)|Lucy Beaumont]] as Mrs. Winship\n*[[Otto Hoffman]] as Sandy, Lombard's servant\n*[[Florence Lawrence]]\n\n==Box Office==\nAccording to Warner Bros records the film earned $348,000 domestically and $37,000 foreign.<ref name=\"warners\"/>\n\n==Preservation status==\nThis film still survives at [[George Eastman House]] and [[Pacific Film Archive]].<ref>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.mbrs.sfdb.1458/default.html The Library of Congress American Silent Feature Film Survival Catalog: ''Lucretia Lombard'']</ref> It was transferred onto 16mm film by [[Associated Artists Productions]]<ref>[https://archive.org/details/mediahistory&tab=collection?and%5B%5D=subject%3A%22Motion%20pictures%20--%20Catalogues%22 1957 Movies from AAP Warner Bros Features & Cartoons, Sales Book Directed at TV]</ref> in the 1950s and shown on television.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Lucretia Lombard}}\n*{{IMDb title|0014229}}\n*{{allmovie|100669|Synopsis}}\n\n{{Jack Conway}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lucretia Lombard}}\n[[Category:1923 films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jack Conway]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Harry Rapf]]\n[[Category:1920s drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Surviving American silent films]]\n\n{{1920s-silent-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucretia_Lombard"}
